<DIV1>
<PB REF="3">
<HEAD>THE HEIR AT LAW.</HEAD>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<STAGE>SCENE I.&mdash;<HI>Room in</HI> LORD DUBERLY'S <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE>LORD DUBERLY <HI>and</HI> LADY DUBERLY <HI>di&s;covered at Breakfa&s;t.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>LORD DUBERLY.</SPEAKER>
<P>BUT what does it matter, my Lady, whether I drink my tea out of a cup or a &s;aucer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A great deal, in the polite circles, my Lord. We have been rai&s;ed by a &s;trange freak of fortune, from nothing, as a body may &s;ay; and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing! As reputable a trade as any in all Go&s;port. You hold a merchant as cheap as if he trotted about with his property in a pack, like a pedlar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A merchant, indeed! Curious merchandize you dealt in, truly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A large a&s;&s;ortment of articles:&mdash;Coals, cloth, herrings, linens, candles, eggs, &s;ugar, treacle, tea, bacon, and b$ick du&s;t; with many more, too tedious to mention in this here adverti&s;ement.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, prai&s;e the bridge that carried you over; but, you mu&s;t now drop the trade&s;man, and learn life. Con&s;ider, by the &s;trange&s;t accident, you have been rai&s;ed to&mdash;neither more nor le&s;s than a peer of the realm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well; but I han't been a nobleman more nor a week; and my throat isn't noble enough yet to be proof again&s;t &s;calding. Hand over the milk, my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hand over! oh, what's bred in the bone will never come out of the fle&s;h, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="4" REF="4">
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! there's a fu&s;s indeed! when I was plain Daniel Dowla&s;s, of Go&s;port, I was reckoned as cute a dab in di&s;cour&s;e as any in our town, nobody found fault with me; my thoughts were like a fat plough&punc;man's chub|by children. If folks found them fre&s;h and &s;trong enough, no matter how they were clothed. But people, I take it, fancy a great Lord's thoughts, are like his ricketty brats&mdash;plaguy weak, and damned ordinary; and want a deal of dre&s;&s;ing up to make 'em pa&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why &s;o loud?&mdash;I declare the &s;ervants will hear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hear! and what will they hear but what they know? our &s;tory a &s;ecret, Lord help you!&mdash;tell 'em Queen Anne's dead, my Lady. Don't every body know that old Lord Duberly was &s;uppo&s;ed to die without any heir to his e&s;tate&mdash;as the Doctors &s;ay, of an implication of di&s;orders; and, that his &s;on, Henry Moreland, was lo&s;t &s;ome time ago, in the &s;alt &s;ea.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, there's no occa&s;ion to&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't every body know that Lawyer Ferret, of Fernival's Inn, owed the Legatees a grudge&mdash;and pop'd a bit of an adverti&s;ement into the News? "Whereas, if the Heir at Law, if there be any reviving, of the late Ba|ron Duberly, will apply&mdash;&s;o, and &s;o; he'll hear of &s;om'ut greatly to his advantage."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why, bawl it to the&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't he hunt me out to &s;ecure my title? and lug me from the counter, to clap me into a coach? a hou&s;e here, in Hanover-&s;quare, and an e&s;tate in the country, worth fifteen thou&s;and per annum?&mdash;Why, ble&s;s you, my Lady, every little black devil, with a &s;oot-bag, cries it about the &s;treets, as often as he &s;ays &s;weep.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis a pity but my Lord had left you &s;ome manners, with his money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>He, what my cou&s;in twenty thou&s;and times removed, he mu&s;t have left them by word of mouth.&mdash;Never &s;poke to him but once, in all my born life, upon electioneering matter&mdash;that's a time when mo&s;t of your proud folks make no bones of tippling with a tallow-chan|dler, in his back-room, on a melting day: but he!&mdash;ex|cept calling me cou&s;in, and buying a lot of damaged huck|aback, to cut into kitchen towels, he was as old and &s;tiff as he is now, tho' he has been dead and buried the&s;e nine months, rot him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, again, now!&mdash;Rot him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, blood and thunder! what is a man to &s;ay, when he wants to con&s;ecrate his old &s;tiff-rumped relations?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="5" REF="5">
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, an oath, now and then, may &s;lip in to garni&s;h genteel conver&s;ation: but then it &s;hould be done with an air to one's equals, and with a kind of carele&s;s conde&s;cen&s;ion to menials.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Should it?&mdash;well then&mdash;here John&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter Servant.</STAGE>
<P>my good man, take away the tea and be damn'd to you?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lord.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit Servant.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And now, my lord, I mu&s;t leave you for the concerns of the day, we elegant people are as full of bu&s;i|ne&s;s as an egg's full of meat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, we elegant people find the trade of the tone, as they call it, plaguy fataguing&mdash;What, are you for the <HI>wis-a-was</HI> this morning? much good may do you, my lady,&mdash;damn it, it makes me &s;it &s;tuck up like a bear in a bathing tub.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have a hundred places to call at&mdash;Folks are &s;o civil &s;ince we came up to take po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion&mdash;there's dear Lady Littlefigure, Lord Sponge, Mrs. Heldbank, Lady Betty Pillory, the Hon. Mrs. Cheatwell, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye; you may always find plenty, in this here town, to be civil to 15,000 a year, my Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, there's no learning you life. I'm &s;ure they are as kind and friendly&mdash;the &s;upper Lady Betty gave to us and a hundred friends, mu&s;t have co&s;t her fifty good pounds, if it co&s;t a bra&s;s farden; and &s;he does the &s;ame thing, I'm told, three times a week. If &s;he isn't mon&s;trous rich, I wonder, for my part, how &s;he can afford it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, ecod, my lady, that would have puz|zled me too, if they hadn't hooked me into a damn'd game of cocking and punting, I think they call it, where I lo&s;t as much in half-an-hour, as would keep her and her com|pany in frica&s;&s;ee's and whipt &s;ullibub's for a fortnight. But I may be even with her &s;ome other a'ternoons. Only let me catch her at put,&mdash;that's all.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JOHN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor Panglo&s;s, is below, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Odds bubs! my Lady, that's the man as larn$ me to talk Engli&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h, con&s;ider.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hum! I forgot&mdash;cur&s;e me, my hone&s;t fellow, &s;hew him up &s;tairs d'ye hear?&mdash;<STAGE>[exit John.]</STAGE>&mdash;There&mdash;was that ea&s;y?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tolerable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="6" REF="6">
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, now, get along, my lady. The doctor and I mu&s;t be &s;nug?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, I bid you a good morning, my Lord, as Lady Betty &s;ays, I wi&s;h you a <HI>bone repos.</HI></P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>A bone repo&s;e!</HI> I don't know how it is, but the woman are more cuter at the&s;e here matters, nor the men. My wife, as every body may &s;ee, is as genteel al|ready, as if &s;he'd been born a dutche&s;s. This doctor Panglo&s;s will do me a great deal of good, in the way of fa&s;hioning my di&s;cour&s;e, &s;o here he is,&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS.</STAGE>
<P>Doctor, good morning&mdash;I wi&s;h you a <HI>bone repos!</HI>&mdash;Take a chair, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, my Lord; I am not inclined to be &s;edentary, I would with permi&s;&s;ion, <HI>"erectos ad &s;idera toll$re vultus."</HI>&mdash;Ovid.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Tollery vultures!</HI> I &s;uppo&s;e that means you rather &s;tand?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fye, this is a locomotive morning with me.&mdash;Ju&s;t hurried, my Lord, from the Society of Arts; whence, I may &s;ay, <HI>"I have borne my blu&s;hing honours thick upon me."</HI>&mdash;Shake&s;peare.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what has put your honor to the blu&s;h, this morning, doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>To the blu&s;h?&mdash;A ludicrous perver&s;ion of the author's meaning.&mdash;He, he, he!&mdash;Hem!&mdash;you &s;hall hear, my Lord.&mdash;<HI>"Lend me your ears."</HI>&mdash;Shake&s;peare, again.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;'Tis not unknown to your Lord&s;hip, and the no le&s;s literary world, that the Caledonion Univer&s;ity of Aberdeen, long &s;ince conferred upon me the dignity of L. L. D.&mdash;and as I never beheld that erudite body, I may &s;afely &s;ay, they dubb'd me with a degree, from &s;heer con&s;i|deration of my celebrity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>True.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>For nothing, my Lord, but my own innate mode&s;ty, could &s;uppo&s;e the Scotch College to be &s;wayed by one pound, fifteen &s;hillings, and three pence, three far|things, paid on receiving my <HI>diploma,</HI> as a hand&s;ome compli|ment to the numerous and learned heads of that Seminary.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, damn it, no; it wasn't for the matter of money</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do not think it was altogether the <HI>"auri &s;acra fames."</HI>&mdash;Virgil&mdash;Hem!&mdash;But this very day, my Lord, at eleven o'clock, A. M. the Society of Arts, in con&s;equence, as they were plea&s;ed to &s;ay, of my merits,&mdash;he, he, he!&mdash;have admitted me an unworthy member; and
<PB N="7" REF="7">
I have, henceforward, the privilege of adding to my name the enviable title of A. double S.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I make no doubt, doctor, but you have rightly de&s;erved it. I warrant a man don't get A. double S. tacked to his name for nothing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Decidedly not, my Lord.&mdash;Yes, I am now <HI>Artium Societatis Socius.</HI>&mdash;My two la&s;t publications did that bu&s;ine&s;s.&mdash;<HI>"Ex&ecirc;gi monumentum aere perennius."</HI>&mdash;Horace.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what might the&s;e two books be about, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The fir&s;t, my Lord, was a plan to lull the re&s;tle&s;s to &s;leep by an infu&s;ion of opium into their ears:&mdash;the efficacy of this method originally &s;truck me in St. Ste|phen's chapel, while li&s;tening to the oratory of a worthy country gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wonder it wasn't hit upon before, by the Doctors.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Phy&s;icians, my Lord, put their patients to &s;leep in another manner. He, he, he!&mdash;<HI>"To die&mdash;to &s;leep&mdash;no more"</HI>&mdash;Shake&s;peare.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;My &s;econd treati&s;e was a propo&s;al for erecting Dove-hou&s;es, on a principle, tending to create the propagation of pigeons. This, I may affirm, has received con&s;iderable countenance from many who move in the circles of fa&s;hion.&mdash;<HI>"Nec gem&euml;re ce&s;&s;abit turtur."</HI>&mdash;Virgil.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I am about to publi&s;h a third edition by &s;ub&s;cription. May I have the honour to pop your Lord&s;hip down among the pigeons?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye; down with me, Doctor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, I am grateful. I ever in&s;ert names and titles at full length. What may be your Lord|&s;hip's &s;pon&s;orial and patronymick appellations?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean, My Lord, the de&s;ignations given to you, by your Lord&s;hip's godfathers and parents.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, what, my chri&s;tian and &s;urname?&mdash;I was bapti&s;ed Daniel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>"Ab$lens bapti&s;m&agrave;te l$bum."</HI>&mdash;I forgot, where&mdash;Hem! The Right Honourable Daniel&mdash;<STAGE>(writing.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dowlas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Writing.)</STAGE> Dowla&s;s.&mdash;<HI>"Filthy Dow."</HI>&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Shake&s;peare.&mdash;The Right Honourable Daniel Dowlas, Baron Duberly.&mdash;And, now, my Lord, to our le&s;&s;on for the day..</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now for it, Doctor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The proce&s;s which we are now upon, is to eradicate that blemi&s;h in your Lord&s;hip's language which
<PB N="8" REF="8">
the learned denomidate <HI>cacology,</HI> and which the vulgar call, &s;lip&punc;&s;lop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'am afraid, Doctor, my <HI>Cakelology</HI> will give you a tolerable tight job of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>"Nil de&s;perandum."</HI> Virgil.&mdash;Hem! We'll begin in the old way, my Lord. Talk on;&mdash;when you &s;tumble, I check. Where was your Lord&s;hip ye&s;terday evening?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>At a <HI>Con&s;ort.</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Umph! <HI>t&ecirc;te &aacute; t&eacute;te,</HI> with Lady Duberly, I pre|&s;ume.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, <HI>t&egrave;te &aacute; t&ecirc;te,</HI> with five hundred people, hearing mu&s;ic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I conceive.&mdash;Your Lord&s;hip would &s;ay, a Concert.&mdash;Mark the di&s;tinction.&mdash;A Concert, my Lord, is an entertainment vi&s;ited by fa&s;hionable lovers of harmo|ny. Now a Con&s;ort is a Wife; little conducive to harmo|ny, in the pre&s;ent day, and &s;eldom vi&s;ited by a Man of Fa&s;hion, unle&s;s &s;he happens to be his friends or his neigh|bours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A devil of a difference, indeed! Between you and I, Doctor&mdash;now my Lady's out of hearing, a wife is the devil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>He, he, he!&mdash;There are plenty of Jobs in the world, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And a damned &s;ight of Jezabels, too, Doctor. But patience, as you &s;ay&mdash;for I never give my Lady no bad language. Whenever &s;he gets in her tantrums, and talks high, I always &s;it mum-chance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>"So &s;pake our mother, Eve, and Adam heard."</HI> Milton.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Silence is mo&s;t &s;ecure, my Lord, in the&s;e ca&s;es; for if once your Lord&s;hip opened your mouth, 'tis twenty to one, but bad language would follow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, that's a &s;ure thing; and I never like to di&s;per&s;e the woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>A&s;per&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Humph! There's another &s;tumble!&mdash;After all, Doctor, I &s;hall make but a poor progre&s;s in my <HI>ver|micular</HI> tongue.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your knowledge of our native, or <HI>vernacu|lar</HI> language, my Lord, time and indu&s;try may meliora$e. Vermicular is an epithet &s;eldom applied to tongues, except in the ca&s;e of puppies who want to be wormed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ecod, then, I'ant &s;o much out, Doctor; I've met plenty of puppies, &s;ince I came to town&mdash;who&s;e tongues are &s;o very trouble&s;ome, that worming might chance to be of &s;ervice.&mdash;But, Dr. I've a bit of a propo&s;al to make to you, concerning of my own family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;clo&s;e, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="9" REF="9">
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you mu&s;t know, I expect my &s;on, Dicky, in town this here very morning. Now, Doctor, if you would mend his <HI>cakelology,</HI> mayhap it might be bet|ter worth than the mending of mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;mell a pupil. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> Whence, my Lord, does the young gentleman come?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall hear all about it: You know, Doctor, tho' I'm of a good family <HI>di&s;traction</HI>&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ex.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tho' I'm of a good family extraction&mdash;'twas but t'other day I kept a &s;hop at Go&s;port.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The rumour has reached me.&mdash;<HI>"Fama volat, vire&s;que."</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't put me out?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Virgil.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Proceed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A trade&s;man, you know, mu&s;t mind the main chance, &s;o when Dick-began to grow as big as a porpus, I got an old friend of mine, who lives in Derby&s;hire, clo&s;e to the Devil's&mdash;hum! clo&s;e to the peak, to take Dick 'pren|tice, at half price.&mdash;He's ju&s;t now out of his time, and I warrant him, as wild and rough as a rock; now, if you doctor&mdash;if you would but take him in hand, and &s;often him a bit&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, my Lord&mdash;<HI>"To &s;often rocks!"</HI> Congreve.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Pray, my Lord, what profe&s;&s;ion may the Honourable Mr. Dowlas have followed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who, Dick? He &s;erved his clerk&s;hip to an attorney, at Ca&s;tleton,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>An Attorney!&mdash;Gentlemen of his profe&s;|&s;ion, my Lord, are very difficult to &s;often.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, but the pay may make it worth the while; I'm told that Lord Spindle gives his elde&s;t &s;on's, ma&s;ter Drum&s;tick's tutorer, three hundred a year; and be&s;ides learning his pupil, he has to read my lord to &s;leep of an afternoon, and walk out with the lap-dogs and chil|dren. Now, if three hundred a year, doctor, will do the bu&s;ine&s;s for Dick, I &s;han't begrudge it you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Three hundred a-year!&mdash;&s;ay no more, my Lord. L. L. D. A. double S. and three hundred a-year&mdash;I accept the office.&mdash;<HI>"Verbam Sat."</HI> Horace.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I'll run to my lodgings&mdash;&s;ettle with Mrs. Sudds&mdash;put my wardrobe into a&mdash;No, I've got it all on&mdash;and&mdash;<STAGE>(going.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold! hold! not &s;o ha&s;ty, doctor, I mu&s;t fir&s;t &s;end you for Dick, to the Blue&punc;boar?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Honourable Mr. Dowlas, my pupil, at the Blue-boar!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, in Holborn, as han't fond of telling people good new before-hand, for fear they may be balk'd; Dick knows nothing of my being made a lord.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="10" REF="10">
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Three hundred a year&mdash;I've often wi&s;h'd that I had clear, For life, &s;ix&mdash;no three,&mdash;three hundred.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wrote him&mdash;ju&s;t before I left Go&s;port, to tell him to meet me in London with&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Three hundred pounds a-year. Swift.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>With all &s;peed, upon bu&s;ine&s;s, d'ye mind me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor Panglo&s;s with an income of&mdash;No lap-dogs, my Lord?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but li&s;ten, Doctor: and as I did'nt know where old Ferrett was to make me live in London, I told Dick to be at the Blue-boar this morning, by the &s;tage-coach&mdash;why you don't hear what you are talking about, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, perfectly, my Lord.&mdash;A Blue-boar in a Stage-coach&mdash;with the annuity of&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, &s;tep into my room, Doctor, and I'll give you a letter which you &s;hall carry to the Inn, and bring Dick away with you. I warrant the boy will be ready to jump out of his &s;kin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Skin! jump! zounds, I'm ready to jump out of mine. I follow your Lord&s;hip.&mdash;Oh, Doctor Panglo&s;s, where's your philo&s;ophy now?&mdash;I attend you, my Lord.&mdash;<HI>"aequam memento."</HI> Horace.&mdash;<HI>"Servare mentum."</HI> Hem! Ble&s;s me, I'm all in a flu&s;ter!&mdash;L. L. D. A. double S. and three hundred a&mdash;I attend your Lord&s;hip.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit with Lord Duberly.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;The Blue-boar Inn in Holborn.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZEKIEL HOMESPUN, MISS CECILY HOMESPUN, <HI>and</HI> WAITER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>This way, if you plea&s;e, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>So, here we be at la&s;t, in London; a the&mdash;What be your &s;ign, young man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Blue-boar, Sir; the olde&s;t Inn in Holborn.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Olde&s;t! why, as you do &s;ay, young man, it do &s;eem in a tumble-downi&s;h kind of condition, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll take care of your portmanteau, if you plea&s;e? Dinner's on the table, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Jirking it from him.)</STAGE> No, but you don't tho'.&mdash;I ha' heard o' the tricks o' London, though I ne'er &s;at foot in it, afore. Ma&s;ter Blue-boar, you ha' gotten the wrong &s;ow by the ear, I can tell you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mi&s;s Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>La, brother, Zekiel! I dare &s;ay, the young man's hone&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Haply he may be, Cecily! but the hone&s;t chaps of this town, as I be told, do need a deal of looking a'ter. Where can Dick Dowlas now be a loitering &s;o long in the yard?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="11" REF="11">
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>The gentleman that came up in the coach with you, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes; the gentleman wi' all his cloaths in his hand, tied up in a little blue and white pocket-hand|kerchief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I de&s;ire him to come up, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, be &s;o kind, will you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall, Sir. <STAGE>[Exit Waiter.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I ha' nothing left but this portmanteau, and you, Cecily: If I was to lo&s;e either of you, what would become of poor Zekiel Home&s;pun?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear now! this was the cry all along upon the road. Don't be down-hearted. Brother, there be plenty of ways of getting bread in London.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, plenty, plenty;&mdash;but many of the ways, they do &s;ay, be &s;o foul, and the bread be &s;o dirty, t'would turn a nice &s;tomach, to eat on't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I do declare, it &s;eems a pure place! with a power of rich folks, for certain; for I &s;aw No. 945, upon one of their coach-doors, as we came along; and no doubt on't there be more of them &s;till. I do like it, Zekiel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't ye, now,&mdash;dont ye, Cecily, pray don't ye be &s;o merry! You &s;care me out of my &s;en&s;es&mdash;Think what a charge I have of you, Cecily.&mdash;Father and mother dead&mdash;no kin to help us&mdash;both thrown a top o' the wide world, to &s;eek our fortunes, and only I to take care of ye. Indeed, indeed, I do love you, Cecily! you would break your poor brother's heart, if any harm was to befall you. You would'nt do that, would ye, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I, Zekiel! I would'nt hurt a hair of your head, if I was to be made a Lord Mayor's lady, for it. You have been a kind brother to me, Zekiel; and if I have the luck to get a &s;ervice fir&s;t, I'd work my fingers to the $one to maintain you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bu&s;s me, Cicely&mdash;od rabbit it, girl, I be only chicken hearted on your account.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but let us hope for the be&s;t, Zekiel. Poor father has followed mother to the cold grave, &s;ure enough; and the &s;quire out of &s;pite he owed him, has turned us out Ca&s;tleton farm, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That were bad enough;&mdash;tho' I could ha' &s;tomach'd that&mdash;but damn him! <STAGE>(heaven forgive us)</STAGE> he &s;poke ill o' father's memory. I'd as big a mind to lick '&s;quire, as ever I had in my life&mdash;and then as you &s;ay, to turn us adrift!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>But we are young and &s;trong, brother Zekiel, and able to get our living.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="12" REF="12">
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, that be true enough, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, then, come now, pluck up a &s;pirit?&mdash;be light&s;ome and jovial a bit, Zekiel&mdash;do now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well I&mdash;I'll do my be&s;t&mdash;dang it, if we had but a friend, now.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, hav'nt we?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>None that I know of; baiting Dick Dow|la&s;s, who be come up wi' us, in the Ca&s;tleton coach.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, brother, I &s;ure he'd go thro' fire and water to &s;erve us. He has told me &s;o, Zekiel, fifty good times, the &s;ide of old Dobbin's pond, by moonlight.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, I do know he ha' kep' you company, Cecily. I told him, when father died, that I was agreea|able to his having of you, provided matters got a little &s;moothi&s;h with you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did you? La, Zekiel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dick, be an hone&s;t fellow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That he is, indeed, brother! <STAGE>(Eagerly.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I ha' known him, now, &s;even good years, &s;ince fir&s;t he came to Ca&s;tleton; and we ha' been for all the world, like brothers. Dick be a little rantipoli&s;h, but as generous a lad, as&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DICK DOWLAS, <HI>&s;inging to</HI> ZEKIEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Oh, London is a fine town <STAGE>(&s;inging without)</STAGE> a very famous city&mdash;(take care of my bundle, d'ye hear)&mdash;<STAGE>[Enter]</STAGE>&mdash;where all the &s;treets are paved with gold, and all the maidens pretty."&mdash;Well, &s;han't we have a bit of &s;ome|thing to eat?&mdash;ju&s;t a &s;nack, Zekiel, Cis&mdash;here, you, Waiter&mdash;<STAGE>[Enter Waiter]</STAGE>&mdash;What, Cis, my girl&mdash;get &s;ome cold beef, you&mdash;how do'&s;t do, after the journey? Aye, cold beef&mdash;put down the bundle&mdash;mu&s;tard, vinegar, and all that, you know&mdash;Cis likes a reli&s;h&mdash;<STAGE>[puts Dick's bundle on the table, and Exit.]</STAGE>&mdash;Aye, jump about, my tight fellow. Zounds! how the rumbling of the old coach keeps whirl|ing in my head.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do think, Dick, your head be always a lit|tle upon the whirligig order.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I hadn't got out to take the reins in hands now and then, I &s;hould have been as muzzy as a Methodi&s;t par&s;on. Didn't I knock the tits along, nicely, Cis?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, indeed, Dick; except bumping us up again&s;t the turn-pike gates, we went as pure and plea|&s;ant&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! that was an accident. Well, old Domini ha&s;n't called for me here, yet; can't think what the old boy wants with me in London&mdash;bad news I'm afraid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="13" REF="13">
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, don't you &s;ay &s;o; Dick!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hap what will, Dick, I'll &s;tand by ye. I be as poor as Job; but I'd &s;hare with my friend in misfortune to the la&s;t penny.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tip us your daddle, Zekiel, you've as ten|der a heart as ever got into the tough carca&s;e of a Ca&s;tleton farmer&mdash;yes, the old boy's la&s;t letter but one, told me that things were going on but badly, damn that chandler's &s;hop, bacon, eggs, coals, and candles have laid him low&mdash;a bankruptcy I warrant, and come up to town to white-wa&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And to con&s;ult wi' you, may hap, as you be in the lea&mdash;about the bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Gad then, it will be like con&s;ulting mo&s;t peo|ple in the law, he'll get nothing from me that's &s;atisfactory, old Latitat had as little bu&s;ine&s;s as I had inclination in the practice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but Dick, &s;ure you can do &s;ummit in your calling&mdash;you can draw up a will, or a lea&s;e of a farm, now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can &s;hoot a wild-duck with any lawyer's clerk in the country, I can fling a bar&mdash;play at cricket&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you can: I u&s;ed to notch for you, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can make a bowl of punch&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you can: I u&s;ed to drink it wi' you you do know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can make love&mdash;<STAGE>(To Cis.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you can, Dick!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can catch gudgeons&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye, that be part of your trade.&mdash;Catching o' Gudgeons, be a Lawyer's chiefe&s;t employment, they do &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, now to bu&s;ine&s;s: here's a new&s;paper, that I picked up at the bar; there's &s;omething in it, I think, that will &s;uit Cis&mdash;Read it:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Reading New&s;paper).</STAGE> "Wanted a Maid"&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's a difficult thing to be met with in Lon|don&mdash;I take it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>So far 'twill do for our Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;I d better make ha&s;te and get the place, for fear any thing &s;hould happen, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Le$'s read it out, Cecily&mdash;"Wanted, "a Maid. Servant&mdash;by a young lady"&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, a young Lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P><Q>&startq;Who lives very retired at the We&s;t end of the town&mdash;&s;he mu&s;t be clean in her per&s;on&endq;</Q>&mdash;Ce|cily be very clean.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>As any la&s;s in Derby&s;hire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="14" REF="14">
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>"And good natured."&mdash;Cecily be as good|natured a girl, as ever&mdash;Umph!&mdash;<Q>&startq;and willing to do what is required.&endq;</Q>&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'm very willing, you know, Dick&mdash;a'nt I?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That you are, Cis, ki&s;s me. <STAGE>(Ki&s;&s;es her.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>La, Dick! This will ju&s;t do!&mdash;I'm &s;o plea&s;ed l&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>"If from the country, the better."&mdash;rabbit it, Cecily, this be the very thing!&mdash;tol, de rol, lol! <Q>&startq;or if any farmer, in difficulties from a numerous family, wi&s;hes to put his daughter to a &s;ervice&endq;</Q>&mdash;oh, my poor old father! this is the thing! <Q>&startq;&s;he will meet with the tendere&s;t care from the lady, who has her&s;elf known what it is to be unfortunate.&endq;</Q> Tol de rol, lol! bu&s;s me, Cecily!&mdash;hug me, Dick Dowla&s;s! I &s;hall provide for &s;i&s;ter&mdash;the care next my very heart.&mdash;Tol lol, de rol, lol! Rabbit it! I be ready to choak for joy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear now! This is the rare&s;t luck!&mdash;Live with a young lady! I &s;hall be &s;o great and grand&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And grow rich with good fortune, and forget your poor friends, Cis.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, no, Cecily, be too good for that.&mdash;Forget a poor friend! when &s;uch giddy folks, chance to get a tumble, they may e'en thank them&s;elves if nobody be ready to help 'em up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, I would'nt have &s;aid &s;uch words to you Dick, you know, &s;o you do, if I was to be made a queen it would be my pride, Dick, to &s;hare all my gold with brother and you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Cis, well, I'm &s;orry, faith I am and if ever I or my family &s;hould come to fortune&mdash;but, p&s;haw! damn it, my father keeps a chandler's &s;hop without cu&s;tom.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WAITER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>The cloth's laid for you, in the other room, Gentlemen; you can't dine here.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;o?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>The Church-wardens come to eat a great din|ner, once a month, for the good of the poor&mdash;this is their day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's as they do down with us.&mdash;But I could never find out, why &s;tuffing a churchwarden's guts, was for the good of the poor of the pari&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor I neither, unle&s;s he got a &s;urfeit that car|ried him off, come Zekiel, you &s;hall go pre&s;ently after the place, but fir&s;t let's refre&s;h, what we eat, will be far the good of the poor, I'm certain.&mdash;Cis, your arm,&mdash;take
<PB N="15" REF="15">
my bundle you dog? and don't drop any thing out, for I've nothing to &s;pare, come Cis.</P>
</SP>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.&mdash;<HI>Lady</HI> CAROLINE DORMER'S <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CAROLINE.</STAGE>
<P>I WISH Kenrick were come back. My la&s;t hope hangs upon the an&s;wer he will bring me.&mdash;World! world!&mdash;when af$uence points the tele&s;cope, how clo&s;ely does&punc; it at|tract thy venal inhabitants! how magnified are all thy &s;miles! Let poverty rever&s;e the gla&s;s, far di&s;tant does it ca&s;t them from us, and the features of friend&s;hip are dwin|dled into nothing.&mdash;I hear him coming.</P>
<STAGE><HI>$nter</HI> KENRICK.</STAGE>
<P>Well Kenrick, you have carried the letter?&mdash;</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I have, Mi&s;s Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what an&s;wer from my father's old friend, Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith now your father's old friend, begging your pardon&mdash;an&s;wered like a big black-guard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Surely, Kenrick, he could not look &s;urpri&s;ed at my application?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Faith, he looked for all the world as if he had &s;wallowed a bottle of vinegar. When I was his honour's (your poor decea&s;ed father's) butler, and helped this old friend to good bumpers of madeira, and be-hanged to him; he made clear another &s;ort of a face of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>And has he &s;ent no letter in an&s;wer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not a &s;yllable at this pre&s;ent writing, it was all by verbal word of dirty mouth.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;ulting!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give my compliments to Mi&s;s Caroline Dor|mer,&mdash;&s;ays he,&mdash;and tell her I'm &s;orry for her misfortunes: ble&s;s you &s;ays I,&mdash;but I can't be of the &s;malle&s;t &s;ervice to her: the devil run away with you, think I.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did he a&s;&s;ign no rea&s;on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Och to be &s;ure, an old &s;kin flint, doesn't he always give you plenty of rea&s;ons for being hard-hearted&mdash;'tis fitting he &s;hould, Mi&s;s, becau&s;e the ca&s;e requires it, but, compa&s;&s;ion is compa&s;&s;ion; and that's rea&s;on enough for &s;hewing it, in con&s;cience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what &s;aid he, Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her father, Mr. Dormer's, bankruptcy, &s;aid he&mdash;and a terrible deal of work, too, &s;ays I; for you know&punc;
<PB N="16" REF="16">
Mi&s;s Caroline, my poor old ma&s;ter, re&s;t his &s;oul, was one of the bigge&s;t merchants in the city of London.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>True, Kenrick; but died almo&s;t one of its poore&s;t inhabitants.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's what the old fellow &s;aid: her father has died &s;o involved, &s;ays he, that no prudent man can concern him&s;elf for the daughter, or run the ri&s;que of med|dling with his affairs&mdash;and &s;o he ended with his re&s;pects, and a parcel of palaver to you&mdash;and an offer of half-a-crown to your humble &s;ervant, as an old acquaintance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>And yet had my father's prudence been of his complexion. I doubt, Kenrick, whether this man would, now, have had half-a-crown to offer you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Och, now, if I had but minded to tell him, that&mdash;but I made the half-crown tell it him, as plain as it could &s;peak&mdash;for I threw it upon the old mi&s;er's table, with a great big whack; and by my &s;oul, he never jumped &s;o high at two and &s;ix-pence, before, in all his beggarly born days.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there is no hope from that quarter, Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more hope than there is in a dead coach hor&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would wi&s;h to be alone, Kenrick: pray leave me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leave you! and in grief, Mi&s;s Caroline!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wouldn't have you, my good old man, a witne&s;s to my affliction.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, and was'nt my poor, dear departed wife Judith, your own nur&s;e&mdash;wet and dry, for many a a good year; and is'nt my&s;elf Felix Kenrick, your own fo&s;ter father, that have dandled you in the&s;e old arms, when you were the &s;ize of a dumpling; and will I leave you to take on after this fa&s;hion?&mdash;alone by your&s;elf. <STAGE>(half crying.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray, pray, be &s;ilent, Kenrick! Oh, na|ture! &s;pite of the inequalities which birth, or education have placed between thy children&mdash;&s;till nature with all thy &s;oftne&s;s, I own thee! The tear of an old and faithful &s;ervant, which bedews the ruins of his &s;helter, is an hone&s;t drop that penetrates the heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, cry away my poor dear Mi&s;s Caroline&punc; cry away, I &s;har'd the &s;un&s;hine of your family, and it is but right that I &s;hould go halves in the ruin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>A poor two hundred pounds, Kenrick, are now all that remain to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well come; two hundred pounds, now a-days, are not to be &s;neezed at, con&s;ider how con&s;oling it is, m y
<PB N="17" REF="17">
dear Mi&s;s, to think that with good management, it may be a matter of two years before you are left without a penny in the whole wide world,&mdash;and that's four and twenty ca|lendar months, you know.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Had this hollow friend of my father's exerted him&s;elf, in the wreck of our hou&s;e's fortune, he might probably, have averted the penury which threatens me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Och, if I could but beat humanity into his heart, through his carca&s;e, I'd make him as tender as a &s;ucking pig.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Duberly's death, too, in the moment of my difficulties!&mdash;In him I might &s;till have found a protector.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye; and his brave &s;on, too, the Hon. Henry Moreland, that was to have married you.&mdash;Well, be of good heart, now&mdash;for he's dead!&mdash;the poor drowned youth!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>De&s;i&s;t, Kenrick, I be&s;eech you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, well, now you are unhappy: but you &s;ee, I'm after making you happy: Ju&s;t as the two families had pop'd down, the man of your heart for your hu&s;band, faith pop'd him&s;elf into the decent watery grave!&mdash;I am left the only tender friend you have, to remind you of it&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Remind me no more, Kenrick, your intention is good; but this is torment to me, in&s;tead of&mdash;<STAGE>[Zekiel &s;peaks without.]</STAGE> Above &s;tairs? oh, very well, Ma'am&mdash;thank you, Ma'am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Croline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hark! I hear&mdash;I hear &s;omebody enquiring for me, on the &s;tairs.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, what's the wor&s;t of the&s;e lodgings, faith people come into your hou&s;e, before you have opened the door. <STAGE>[A knock at the Door.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come in?</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZEKIEL <HI>and</HI> CECILY.</STAGE>
<P>have you any bu&s;ine&s;s with me friend?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, yes, madam,&mdash;it be a &s;malli&s;h bit of bu&s;ine&s;s, as a body, may &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, young man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, yes, ma'am, I become to&mdash;pray, if I may make &s;o bold, isn't your name, A. B?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I under&s;tand, you come in con&s;equence of an adverti&s;ement.&mdash;I believe you may leave us, Ken|rick, <STAGE>(exit Kenrick)</STAGE> it was I who adverti&s;ed for a &s;ervant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And with permi&s;&s;ion, Madam, I be come to offer for the place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>You, hone&s;t friend, as a Maid Servant!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;for Cecily&mdash;Curt'&s;ey, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do, brother, Zekiel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="18" REF="18">
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>This be my &s;i&s;ter, Ma'am&mdash;We be newly come from Derby&s;hire:&mdash;and lighting at the Blue-boar&mdash;the great Inn, in&mdash;Holborn&mdash;that&mdash;but, perhaps, you may frequent it, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why we &s;tumbled upon your notice in the news, Madam&mdash;and &s;o&mdash;and &s;o here we be, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you ever been in &s;ervice, before child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, never, if you plea&s;e, Madam.&mdash;I was always with father, and minded the dairy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>And why did you quit your father, pray?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>He died, if you plea&s;e, Madam. It was a &s;ad day for brother and I. 'Tis a cruel thing to lo&s;e a good father, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is, indeed, child. I can well feel it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when he dies in di&s;tre&s;s, too, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Did <HI>your</HI> father die &s;o, child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>All along o' that damned Squire.&mdash;Mother ware gone long ago:&mdash;and when children be left de&s;titute, it be hard to find a friend to compa&s;&s;ionate 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>I&mdash;I will be that friend.&mdash;My power is little&mdash;almo&s;t nothing; but as far as it can go, you &s;hall find a protection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the gracious!&mdash;what a pure lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>But can you refer me to any one for a character?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I ha' gotten a character in my pocket, Ma'am. They tell me that be the way they do take mo&s;t characters in London.&mdash;Here be a certificate from Par&s;on Brock, of our pari&s;h.&punc; <STAGE>(Giving it.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>See, what can you do to be u&s;eful, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, a power of things;&mdash;I can churn and feed the ducks, milk cows, and fatten a pig, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, you will find &s;i&s;ter Cecily handy, I warrant her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>All the&s;e will be of little &s;ervice in London.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Od rabbir it! madam, &s;he will &s;oon learn here, to put her hand to any thing.&mdash;Won't you, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I don't, it &s;han't be for want of inclina|tion,&mdash;So plea&s;e you, my lady!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, child, come in the evening, and you &s;hall begin your &s;ervice. We &s;hall not di&s;agree about wages; and you will be treated more like an humble friend, than a &s;ervant. Kenrick!&mdash;I &s;hall have only your&s;elf and a poor faithful Iri&s;hman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>An Iri&s;hman! dang it, the&s;e Iri&s;hmen, as I've been told, be devils among the girls, my mind do mi&s;give me; for Cecily be young and thoughtle&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="19" REF="19">
<HI>Enter</HI> KENRICK.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shew the&s;e good people down, Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall do that thing, Mi&s;s Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, then this be the Iri&s;hman. He be a plaguy old one, indeed! come, there be nothing to fear about he. A good day to you, Madam.&mdash;Curt'&s;ey, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, you two go fir&s;t; for I mu&s;t be after &s;hewing you the way, you know. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>This &s;imple girl's &s;tory approach$s &s;o near to my own, that it touches me. Poor innocence! mine is a &s;orry &s;helter in your wanderings; yet it may be warmer than one more &s;plendid. For&mdash;opulence relieves &s;ometimes with coldne&s;s, &s;ometimes with oftentation, &s;ometimes with levity: but &s;ympathy kindles the brighte&s;t &s;park that &s;hines on the altar of compa&s;&s;ion; and tenderne&s;s pours on it the &s;weete&s;t balm that charity produces, when the afflicted ad|mini&s;ter to the afflicted. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.&mdash;<HI>An Inn.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS <HI>and</HI> WAITER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let the chariot turn about.&mdash;Doctor Panglo&s;s in a Lord's chariot!&mdash;<HI>"Curru por-tatur eodem."</HI> Juve|nal.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Waiter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Have you any gentleman here, who arrived this morning in the Stage?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>There's one in the hou&s;e, now, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is he juvenile?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, Sir; he's Derby&s;hire.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>He, he, he!&mdash;Of what appearance is the gentleman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, plaguy poor, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>"I hold him rich, had he not a &s;hirt."</HI>&mdash;Chau|cer.&mdash;Hem! Denominated the honourable Mr. Dowlas?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Honourable!&mdash;he le&s;t his name plain Dowlas, at the bar, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plain Dowlas, did he? That will do: <HI>"for all the re&s;t is leather"</HI>&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>Leather, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>"And Prunello."</HI> Pope.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Tell Mr. Dowlas a gentleman reque&s;ts the honour of an interview.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit Waiter.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never before did honour and affluence, let $all &s;uch a &s;hower on the head of Doctor Panglo&s;s!&mdash;Fortune, I thank thee&punc;&mdash;Propitious Godde&s;s, I am grateful!&mdash;I, thy ill-favoured child&mdash;who commenced his career in the
<PB N="20" REF="20">
loftie&s;t apartment of a muffin-maker, in Milk-alley&mdash;"lit|tle did I think, good ea&s;y man"&mdash;Shake&s;peare&mdash;of the riches and literary dignities which now&mdash;<STAGE>(Enter Dick)</STAGE>&mdash;my pupil!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, where is the man that wants&mdash;oh, you are he, I &s;uppo&s;e&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I <HI>am</HI> the man, young gentleman.&mdash;<HI>"Homo Sum."</HI> Terence.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Sir, the per&s;on who now pre|&s;umes to addre&s;s you, is Peter Panglo&s;s, to who&s;e name, in the College of Aberdeen, is &s;ubjoined L. L. D. &s;ignifying Doctor of Laws; to which has been recently added, the di&s;tinction of A. double S.&mdash;the Roman initials for Fellow of the Society of Arts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I'm your mo&s;t obedient, Richard Dow|las; to who&s;e name, in his Taylor's bill, is &s;ubjoined, D. R. &s;ignifying Debtor, to which are added, L. S. D. the Roman initials for Pounds, Shillings, and Pence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! this youth was doubtle&s;s de&s;igned by de&s;tiny to move in the circles of fa&s;hion; for he's dipt in debt, and makes a merit of telling it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But what are your commands with me, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have the honor, young gentleman, of be|ing deputed as Emba&s;&s;ador to you, from your father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then you have the honour to be Amba&s;&s;ador of as good-natured an old fellow, as ever &s;old a halfpenny|worth of chee&s;e in a chandler's &s;hop.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, if on the &s;ubject of your father's chee&s;e, I advi&s;e you to be as mute as a mou&s;e in one, for the future. 'Twere better to keep that <HI>"alta menta re|po&s;tum."</HI> Virgil.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what's the matter?&mdash;any misfortune? broke, I fear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>No; not broke; but his name, as 'tis cu&s;to|mary in the&s;e ca&s;es, has appeared in the Gazette.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not broke, but Gazetted&mdash;why Zounds! and the Devil!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Check your pa&s;&s;ions&mdash;learn philo&s;ophy; when the wife of the great Socrates threw a&mdash;hum!&mdash;threw a tea-pot at his erudite head, he was as cool as a cucumber.&mdash;When Plato&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn Plato!&mdash;what of my father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't damn Plato&mdash;the bees &s;warmed round his mellifluous mouth, as &s;oon as he was &s;waddled. <HI>"Cum in cunis apes in labellis con&s;edi&s;&s;ent."</HI> Cicero.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you had a &s;warm round your's, with all my heart&mdash;come to the point.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>In due time. But calm your choler.&mdash;<HI>"Ira furor brevis e&s;t."</HI> Horace.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;<STAGE>[Gives a letter.]</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="21" REF="21">
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Snatches it and breaks it open]</STAGE>&mdash;<Q>&startq;Dear Dick, this comes to inform you, I am in a perfect &s;tate of health, hoping you are the &s;ame&endq;</Q>&mdash;Aye, that's the old beginning&mdash;"it was my lot, la&s;t week, to be made"&mdash;a bankrupt, I &s;uppo&s;e&mdash;to be made a&mdash;what?&mdash;to be made "a PEAR!"&mdash;a pear&mdash;to be made a pear!&mdash;what the devil does he mean by that?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>A peer&mdash;a Peer of the realm.&mdash;His Lord|&s;hip's orthography is a little loo&s;e, but &s;everal of his equals countenance the cu&s;tom. Lord Loggerhead always &s;pells Phy&s;ician with an F.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>[Reads on.]</STAGE> "A Peer!"&mdash;what, my father? I am electrified&mdash;old Daniel Dowlas made a Peer of the Realm?&mdash;"Lawyer Ferroll got me my tittle"&mdash;tittle&mdash;Oh, title;&mdash;<Q>&startq;and an e&s;tate of Fifteen Thou&s;and per an|num; whereby making me out next a-kin to old Lord Duberly, becau&s;e he died without hair.&endq;</Q>&mdash;'Tis an odd rea&s;on, by the bye, to be next a-kin to a nobleman becau&s;e he died bald!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>His Lord&s;hip means heir. We &s;hall melio|rate his &s;tyle &s;peedily. <HI>"Reform it altogether."</HI> Shake|&s;peare.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>"I &s;end my carrot." Carrot!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>He, he, he! Chariot his Lord&s;hip means.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>"With Doctor Panglo&s;s in it."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Re&s;pect him; for he's an L. L. D. and moreover an A. double S." <STAGE>Both bows.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>His Lord&s;hip kindly conde&s;cended to in&s;ert that, at my reque&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<Q>&startq;And I have made him your tutorer, to mend your cakelology.&endq;</Q>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Cacology:&mdash;from</HI> Kakos malus and Logos ver|bum.&mdash;vide <HI>Lexicon.&mdash;Hem!</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Come with the Doctor to my hou&s;e, in Hanover-&s;quare."&mdash;Hanover-&s;quare!&mdash;<Q>&startq;&endq;I remain your af|fectionate father to command,</Q></P>
<STAGE>DUBERLY."</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's his Lord&s;hip's title.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Say Sir, to a Lord's &s;on. You have no more manners than a Bear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Bear! under favour, young gentleman, I am the bear-leader; being appointed your Tutor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what can you teach me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prudence&mdash;don't forget your&s;elf in &s;udden &s;ucce&s;s. <HI>"Tecum habita."</HI> Per&s;ais.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="22" REF="22">
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Prudence to a Nobleman's &s;on, with fifteen thou&s;and a year.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't give way to your pa&s;&s;ions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Give way&mdash;Zounds! I'm wild&mdash;mad&mdash;you teach me&mdash;pooh&mdash;I've been in London before, and know it requires no teaching to be a modern fine gentleman&mdash;why it all lies in a nut&s;hell:&mdash;Sport a curricle&mdash;walk Bond-&s;treet&mdash;play at Faro&mdash;get drunk&mdash;dance reels&mdash;go to the Opera&mdash;cut off your tail&mdash;pull on your pantaloons&mdash;and there's a buck of the fir&s;t fa&s;hion in town for you&mdash;Damme! d'ye think I don't know what's going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on me! I &s;hall have a very refractory pupil!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not at all; we'll be hand and glove together. My little Doctor, I'll drive you down to all the races, with my terrier between your legs, in a tandem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor Panglo&s;s, the philo&s;opher, with a terrier between his legs in a tandem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you what, Doctor&mdash;I'll make you my long &s;top, at cricket&mdash;you &s;hall draw corks, when I'm pre|&s;ident&mdash;laugh at my joke before company&mdash;&s;queeze lemons for punch&mdash;ca&s;t up the reckoning&mdash;and woe betide you, if you don't keep &s;ober enough to &s;ee me &s;afe home after a jollification.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Make me a long &s;top, and a &s;queezer of le|mons!&mdash;Zounds! this is more fatiguing than walking out with the lap dogs! and are the&s;e the qualifications for a Tutor, young gentleman?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure, they are. It's the way that half the prig par&s;ons, who educate us Honourables, jump into &s;at livings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis well they jump into &s;omething fat at la&s;t, for they mu&s;t wear all the fle&s;h off their bones in the proce&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick. D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, now, tutor, go you, and call the waiter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go, and call!&mdash;Sir, Sir!&mdash;I'd have you to under&s;tand, Mr. Dowlas&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, let us under&s;tand one another, doctor, my father, I take it, comes down hand&s;omely to you, for your management of me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord has been liberal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But, 'tis I mu&s;t manage you, doctor, ac|knowledge this, and between our&s;elves, I'll find means to double your pay.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Double my&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you he&s;itate&mdash;why, man, you have &s;et up for a modern tutor, without knowing your trade?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Double my pay!&mdash;&s;ay no more&mdash;Done.&mdash;<HI>"actum e&s;t."</HI> Terence.&mdash;'Gad I've reached the right read|ing at la&s;t&mdash;</P>
<P><PB N="23" REF="23">
"I've often wi&s;h'd that I had clear,</P>
<P>"For life, <HI>&s;ix</HI> hundred pounds a year."&mdash;Swift.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Waiter!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> WAITER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right, tell him to pop my cloaths and linen into the carriage, they are in that bundle?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here, put all the Honourable Mr. Dowlas's cloaths and linen into his father's, Lord Duberly's, chariot.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Waiter.</SPEAKER>
<P>All,&mdash;where are they, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>All wrapt up in the Honourable Mr. Dow|las's pocket-handkerchief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>See them &s;afe in, doctor, and I'll be with you pre&s;ently?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I go, mo&s;t worthy pupil. Six hundred pounds a year! However deficient in the cla&s;&s;ics, his knowledge of arithmetick is admirable!&mdash;I've often wi&s;h'd that I had clear, for life&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay, don't be &s;o &s;low?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Swift.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I'm gone. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What am I to do with Zekiel and Cis?&mdash;When a poor man is grown great, his old acquaintance ge|nerally begins to be trouble&s;ome.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ZEKIEL.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I ha'nt been long.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, you are come time enough in all con&s;cience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cecily ha' gotten the place. I be almo&s;t &s;tark wild with joy. Such a good-natured young Madam!&mdash;why you don't &s;eem plea&s;ed, man, &s;ure, and &s;ure you be glad of our good fortune, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what do you? Oh, but he don't know yet, that I am a Lord's &s;on. I rejoice to hear of your &s;ucce&s;s, friend Zekiel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why now, that's hearty.&mdash;But eh?&mdash;Why you look mortal heavy and lumpi&s;h, Dick; no bad tidings &s;ince we ha' been out, I hope?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh?&mdash;Let's ha' a &s;quint at you. Od rabbit, but &s;omething ha' happened. You ha' &s;een your father, and things ha' gone cro&s;&s;ih&mdash;Who have been here, Dick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only a gentleman, who had the honour of being reputed Emba&s;&s;ador from my father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>What a dickens, an Emba&s;&s;ador!&mdash;Pi&s;h, now you be a queering a bodyt An Emba&s;&s;ador &s;ent from an old Chandler to Dick Dowlas, lawyer Latitat's clerk!&mdash;come, that be a good one, fegs!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dick Dowlas! and Lawyer's Clerk!&mdash;Sir, the gentleman came to inform me, that my father by being proved next of kin to the late Lord&mdash;is now Lord Duber|ly; by which means I'm the Hon. Mr. Dowlas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Odds fle&s;h, gi' us your fi&s;t, Dick!&mdash;I ne'er &s;hook the fi&s;t of an honourable afore, in all my born days. Old Daniel made a lord! I be main glad to hear it,&mdash;this be news indeed! but Dick, I hope he ha' gotten &s;ome ready along wi' his title.&mdash;For a lord without money be but a fooli&s;h, wi&s;hy wa&s;hy kind of a thing a'ter all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father's e&s;tate is 15,000l. a year.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy on us! you ha' $a$$n away my breath!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Zekiel, Cis and you &s;hall hear from me &s;oon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why you be'nt a going Dick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t pay my duty to his Lord&s;hip&mdash;his cha|riot waits for me, below. We have been &s;ome-time ac|quainted, Zekiel, and you may depend on my good offices.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>You do &s;eem a little fru&s;trated wi' the&s;e tidings, Dick.&mdash;I &s;hould be loth to think our kindne&s;s was a cooling.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no! rely upon my protection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, look ye, Dick Dowlas; as to pro|tection, and all that, we ha' been old friends, and if I &s;hould need it from you, it be no more nor my right to expect it, and your bu&s;ine&s;s to give it me. But Cecily ha' gotten a place, and I ha' hands and health to get a live|lihood. Fortune, good, or bad, tries the man, they &s;ay&mdash;and if I &s;hould hap to be made a Lord to-morrow (as who can &s;ay what may betide, &s;ince they ha' made one of an old Chandler)&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well &s;ir, and what then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why then, the fine&s;t feather in my lord&s;hip's cap, would be to &s;hew there be as much &s;hame in &s;lighting an old friend, becau&s;e he be poor, as there be plea&s;ure in owning him, when it be out of our power to do him a &s;ervice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You mi&s;take me, Zekiel&mdash;I&mdash;I&mdash;'&s;death&mdash;I'm quite confounded. I'm trying to be as fa&s;hionable as my neighbou$s; but nature comes in, and knocks it all in the head. Zekiel, give me your hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then there be a hearty Ca&s;tleton &s;lap for you. The gra&s;p of an hone&s;t man can't di&s;grace the hand of a Duke, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Dick</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>You're a kind &s;oul. Zekiel, I regard you &s;incerely&mdash;I love Cecily, and&mdash;damn it, I'm going too far now, for a Lord's &s;on. Pride and old friend&s;hip are fight|ing
<PB N="25" REF="25">
in me, 'till I'm almo&s;t bewildered&mdash;you &s;hall hear from me, in a few hours. Good bye, Zekiel; good bye. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know what ails me, but I be almo&s;t ready to cry.&mdash;Dick be a high-mettled youth, and this news ha' put him a little be&s;ide him&s;elf. I &s;hould make a bit of allowance. His heart, I do think, be in the right road, and when that be the ca&s;e, he be a hard judge, that won't pardon an old friends &s;pirits, when they do carry him a little way out on't <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD><HI>SCENE I.</HI>&mdash;A Chamber in an Inn.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> STEDFAST, MORELAND <HI>and</HI> WAITER.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>WAITER.</SPEAKER>
<P>THIS way, gentlemen, if you plea&s;e, this is our be&s;t apartment,&mdash;our hotel provides dinners.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>No chattering?&mdash;We have bu&s;ine&s;s.&mdash;Wel|come, at la&s;t, Mr. Moreland, to London. After wander|ing over foreign lands, with what joy an Engli&s;hman &s;ets his foot on Briti&s;h ground! His heart &s;wells with plea&s;ure as he drives through his fat native &s;oil, which ruddy labour has cultivated; 'till he reaches this grand re&s;ervoir of opu|lence, an opulence which may well make him proud, for its honourable &s;ource is his countrymen's indu&s;try.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>To you, Stedfa&s;t; who have no private fears, no anxieties for your family, the &s;atisfaction mu&s;t be exqui&s;ite.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I'm an old batchelor, 'tis true&mdash;and without relations; but the whole country is my family.&mdash;I could not help thinking, as we po&s;ted to town, that every jolly pea&s;ant, and every cherry cheek'd la&s;s, was a kind of humble brother and &s;i&s;ter to me; and they called forth my affections accordingly. Rich or poor, great or &s;mall, we all form one chain Henry: May the larger and le&s;&s;er links hold kindly together, 'till time &s;lides into eternity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>A truce to the&s;e reflections now, my dear Stedfa&s;t.&mdash;They do your heart honour, but mine is filled with a thou&s;and apprehen$ions&mdash;my father!&mdash;my Caroline!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>A father and a mi&s;tre&s;s! duty and love, that's a &s;low fire, and a fierce blazc; and doubt blowing the bellows upon 'em. 'Tis enough to &s;corch a young &s;oul to a cinder,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis &s;trange I never heard from either of them. After e&s;caping the perils of &s;hipwreck! After the &s;uffer|ings' that followed&mdash;a father, a mi&s;tre&s;s, &s;oon to be made
<PB N="26" REF="26">
a wife, might &s;urely have &s;ent one line to te&s;tify their plea&s;ure at my pre&s;ervation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, now make your&s;elf mi&s;erable, a young mind is too &s;oon &s;anguine, and therefore too &s;oon depre&s;&s;ed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why what can be the rea&s;on they have never an&s;wered my letters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Um! there is one rea&s;on, indeed, that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>You alarm me!&mdash;What can that be?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>That they have never received them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing more likely; con&s;ider, your la&s;t let|ter from Quebec, told your father, Lord Duberly, that you had avenged all the bu&s;ine&s;s which had call'd you there, and that in three days you &s;hould embark for England.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, that he never an&s;wered.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't tell&mdash;probably not. Mo&s;t people think it &s;omewhat &s;uperfluous to write to a corre&s;pondent at Quebec, after he has left the place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw! I'm bewildered.&mdash;But &s;ince&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why &s;ince, the chances have been again&s;t you.&mdash;Wreck'd on our pa&s;&s;age&mdash;thrown upon the uninha|bited part of the i&s;land of Cape Breton&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall never think of it without horror, nor without gratitude, Stedfa&s;t. To your friendly care, &s;tran|gers as we then were to each other, in that frozen &s;hore of de&s;olation, I owe my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!&mdash;non&s;en&s;e&mdash;We both met as fellow|pa&s;&s;engers, and were fellow-&s;ufferers; I happened to be the toughe&s;t, that's all.&mdash;I do as we would be done by, is merely a part of our duty!&mdash;But, there's &s;o much fu&s;s about it, now, that, I'm afraid the duty is too often ne|glected.&mdash;I &s;uppo&s;e we &s;hall &s;oon thank our &s;hoe-black for bru&s;hing our boots, though we reward him for the bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet humanity, Stedfa&s;t&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is every man's bu&s;ine&s;s, and the reward he will ultimately receive for it as far above human calcula|tion. But come, thank providence, and not me.&mdash;To furvive at the end of two months, when mo&s;t of the &s;mall parcel of our comrades were dead, or dying about us, with cold and hunger, is no common e&s;cape.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>And then in a de&s;perate hope to launch our &s;hat|tered boat in que&s;t of an inhabited country, and to be to&s;&s;ed about for two months more, 'till benumbed and pe|ri&s;hing, we were di&s;covered by the natives and friendly Indians.&mdash;All this, Stedfa&s;t, was indeed a &s;tout trial.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then away with $rifling fears, now, &s;ince our deliverance, we have changed our ground, daily, on our
<PB N="27" REF="27">
turn to England, the time&mdash;the di&s;tance&mdash;your letters&mdash;theirs&mdash;all may have mi&s;carried.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>May it prove &s;o. But let me ha&s;ten to my fa|ther's and clear my doubts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, &s;tay, &s;tay. You know 'twas at my reque&s;t you drove to this hotel; now pray, at my reque&s;t let me wait on Lord Duberly, to prepare him for your ap|pearance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>For what purpo&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>A very evident one. The wreck of our &s;hip, has doubtle&s;s, long been public in London. And as the c$ew and pa&s;&s;engers are probably all &s;uppo&s;ed to have pe|ri&s;hed, your abrupt entrance at your father's, might be too much for him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are perfectly right. In the moment when our pa&s;&s;ions are afloat, how beneficial is the cool advice of a friend to direct us. But &s;houldn't I give you a line of introduction to my father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Umph! why according to u&s;ual form, indeed&mdash;but I was never good at forms; and, in this ca&s;e, it may be better to let me introduce my&s;elf in my own way. I hope Lord Duberly is no &s;tickler for ceremonies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>He has the manlie&s;t virtue and the warme&s;t heart in the world, my friend, but I confe&s;s to tho&s;e who are unacquainted with them, the&s;e qualities are a little con|cealed by a coldne&s;s in his manner that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I under&s;tand.&mdash;A little &s;tately or &s;o.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only a little of the <HI>veille coeur</HI> about him. A long habit too, of haranguing in Parliament, gives a man a kind of dignity of deportment, and an elevation of &s;tyle not to be met with every day you know. But Gentle|man is written legibly upon his brow; erudition &s;hines thro' every poli&s;hed period of his language; and he is the be&s;t of men, and of fathers, believe me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye. I &s;ee&mdash;I &s;ee.&mdash;Grand and &s;tiff, $ut of &s;terling value, like an old fa&s;hion'd &s;ilver candle|&s;tick.&mdash;Well, I'll &s;oon bring you an account of my em|ba&s;&s;y.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>And while you are at my father's, I'll walk to Mrs. Dormer's; my &s;u&s;pen&s;e about Caroline is intolerable. I mu&s;t &s;ee the good old gentleman, and he will break my arrival to his daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Meet me, then, here, in a couple of hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be it &s;o, a thou&s;and thanks my dear Stedfa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>A thou&s;and fiddle&s;tick! I ha$e to be thank'd a thou&s;and times for a trifle.&mdash;I know 'tis the language of the day; but modern complimentary cant is the coin|age of di&s;hone&s;ty, for the profe&s;&s;ion exceeds the feeling;
<PB N="28" REF="28">
&mdash;and nine men in ten who give it under their hands, that they are your devoted humble &s;ervants, pledge them|&s;elves to you for much more than they ever mean to per|form. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.&mdash;<HI>Lord</HI> DUBERLY'S <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Lady</HI> DUBERLY <HI>di&s;covered with</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And how does my Lord come on in his learn|ing, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Apt&mdash;very apt, indeed, for his age.&mdash;Defec|tive in nothing, now, but words, phra&s;es and grammar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you could learn him to follow my ex|ample, and be a little genteel:&mdash;but there's no making a &s;ilk pur&s;e out of a &s;ow's ear, they &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Time may do much. But, as to my Lord, every body has'nt your Lady&s;hip's exqui&s;ite elegance.&mdash;"Upon my &s;oul a lie." Shake&s;peare&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A mighty pretty &s;poken man!&mdash;and you are made tutorer, I'm told, Doctor, to my Dicky?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>That honour has accrued to your ob&s;equious &s;ervant, Peter Panglo&s;s: I have now the felicity of &s;uper|intending your Lady&s;hip's Dicky.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;tn't have my &s;on thwarted, Doctor&mdash;for when he has his way in every thing, he's the &s;weete&s;t tempered youth in Chri&s;tendom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>An extraordinary in&s;tance of mildne&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, as mild as mother's milk, I a&s;&s;ure you.&mdash;And what is he to learn, doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>D. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Our readings will be various&mdash;Logic, Ethics, and Mathematics; Hi&s;tory, Foreign and Dome&s;tic; Geo|graphy, Ancient and Modern; Voyages and Travels, An|tiquities, Briti&s;h and Foreign, Natural Hi&s;tory, Natural and moral philo&s;ophy, Cla&s;&s;ics, Arts, and Sciences, Belles Lettres, and Mi&s;cellanies.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me! 'tis enough to batter the poor boy's brains to a mummy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>"A little learning"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Little!&mdash;a load!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>"Is a dangerous thing" <HI>Pope.&mdash;Hem!</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you have left out the main article.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What may your Lady&s;hip mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mean!&mdash;Why dancing to be &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Doctor Panglo&s;s, the philo&s;opher, teach to dance!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Between whiles you might give Dick a le&s;|&s;on or two in the hall&mdash;as my lord's valet plays on the
<PB N="29" REF="29">
kit, it will be quite handy to have you both in the hou&s;e, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is a damned barbarous old woman! With &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion to your Lady&s;hip, my bu&s;ine&s;s is with the the head, not with the heels, of my pupil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fiddle faddle! Lady Betty tells me, that the heads of young men of fa&s;hion, now a-days, are by no means overloaded. They are left to the Barber and Denti&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twould be daring to di&s;pute &s;o &s;elf-evident an axiom&mdash;But if your Lady&s;hip&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look ye doctor,&mdash;he mu&s;t learn to dance and jabber French, and I would'nt give a bra&s;s farden for any thing el&s;e&mdash;I know what's elegance, and you'll find the gray mare the better hor&s;e, in this hou&s;e, I promi&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her Lady&s;hip, I perceive, is paramount.&mdash;<HI>"Puz femmina facti"</HI> Virgil.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's your pay here, Mr. tutorer?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Three hundred per annum&mdash;that is&mdash;no, three&mdash;no&mdash;aye, no matter:&mdash;the re&s;t's between me and Mr. Dowlas. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do as I direct you, in private, and, to pre|vent words, I'll double it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Double it! What, again!&mdash;nine hundred per ann! I'll take it!&mdash;<HI>"Your hand, a Covenant."</HI> Shake&s;peare.&mdash;Hem! Zounds! I've got beyond the read|ing at la&s;t!&mdash;"I've often wi&s;h'd that I had clear for life"&mdash;I hear my Lord&mdash;"Nine hundred pounds a year? Swift.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD DUBERLY <HI>and</HI> DICK DOWLAS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along, Dick, here he is again my lady, Twi&s;t, the Taylor, happened to come in promi&s;cou&s;&s;y, as I may &s;ay, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Accidentally, my Lord, would be better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, accidentally&mdash;with a &s;uit of my Lord Docktail's under his arm&mdash;and as we were in a bit of a rumpus, to rig-out Dick, why&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dre&s;s.&mdash;not rig&mdash;unle&s;s metaphorically.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well,&mdash;dre&s;s out,&mdash;why we&mdash;humph! Dr. don't brother. In &s;hort we popt Dick into them,&mdash;and Twi&s;t &s;ays they hit to a hair.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; they are quite the dandy; ar'nt they, mother?&mdash;This is all the go, now, they &s;ay&mdash;cut &s;traight&mdash;that's the thing&mdash;&s;quare wai&s;t&mdash;wrap over the knee, and all that&mdash;&s;louch is the word now!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Exceedingly genteel, I declare! Turn about, Dick; they don't pinch you, do they?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="30" REF="30">
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no! ju&s;t as if I had been mea&s;ured.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pinch! lord love you, my lady, they &s;et like a &s;ack.&mdash;But why don't you &s;tand up? the boy rolls about like a porpus in a &s;torm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The very air and grace of our young no|bility!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's the fa&s;hion father&mdash;that's modern ea&s;e young Oats, the beau brewer, from the boro', brought it down, la&s;t Chri&s;tmas, to Ca&s;tleton. A young fellow is nothing now without the Bond-&s;treet roll, a tooth-pick be|tween his teeth, and his knuckles crammed into his coat-pockets&mdash;then away you go, lounging lazily along&mdash;Oh, Tom&mdash;what Will! Rolling away, you &s;ee&mdash;How are you, Jack?&mdash;What, my little Dolly!&mdash;That's the way&mdash;Isn't it, mother?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it? Grace mu&s;t have got plaguy limber, then, and lopt of late.&mdash;There's the la&s;t lord Duberly's father done in our dining room, with a wig as wide as a wa&s;h-tub, and &s;tuck up as &s;tiff as a poker. He was one of your tip-tops, too, in his time, they tell me:&mdash;he car|ried a gold &s;tick before George the fir&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and looks for all the world as &s;traight as if he &s;wallowed it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter for that, my lady;&mdash;what &s;igni|fies dignity without it's <HI>crakeri&s;tick</HI>&mdash;a man &s;hould know how to bemean him&s;elf, when he is as rich as Pluto.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plutus, if you plea&s;e, my Lord.&mdash;Pluto, no doubt, has di&s;ciples and followers of fa&s;hion; <Q>&startq;But Plu|tus is the ruler of riches.&endq;</Q> He&s;&s;iod.&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>There Dick, d'ye hear how the tutorer talks? oh rabbit it! he can ladle you out of Latin by the quart;&mdash;and grunts greek like a pig. I've gin three hundred a year, and &s;ettled all he's to learn you.&mdash;Han't I, doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Certainly my lord, <HI>"thrice to thine?</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; we know all about that&mdash;don't we, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Decidedly,</HI> "and thrice to thine?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye, clearly under&s;tood&mdash;isn't it, Doc|tor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Undoubtedly, <Q>&startq;&endq;and thrice again to make up nine?</Q> Sheak&s;peare&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JOHN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, there's a Mr. Stedfa&s;t below, wants to &s;peak to you below about particular bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Lord</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;ter Stedfa&s;t! never heard of the name, cur&s;e me, my lad;&mdash;tell him I'll be with him in the twinkling of a bed-po&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lord. <STAGE>[Exit John.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="31" REF="31">
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall go with your Lord&s;hip through the gallery, for I mu&s;t dre&s;s to attend Lady Betty.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come along, then my lady.&mdash;Dick go with the tutorer&mdash;he'll give you a le&s;&s;on in my library&mdash;plenty of learning there! I promi&s;e you. I was looking at it all of a row, this here very morning.&mdash;There's all Horace's Operas, doctor, and &s;uch a &s;ight of French Books! but I &s;ee by the books they are all written by Tom.&mdash;Come along my Lady? <STAGE>[Exit with Lady Duberly.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>On what &s;ubject, Mr. Dowla&s;s, &s;hall we commence on re&s;earches, this evening?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mean to light up the billiard-room&mdash;we'll knock about the balls a little.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Knock about the balls!&mdash;an admirable en|trance upon a cour&s;e of &s;tudies!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do you know any thing of the game?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I know how to pocket, young gentleman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>So do mo&s;t tutors, Doctor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I could but per&s;uade you to peep into a cla&s;&s;ic.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Peep&mdash;why, you prig of a fellow, don't I pay you becau&s;e I won't peep?&mdash;Talk of this again, and I'm off in our contract.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Are you? I'm dumb.&mdash;<HI>"Mammon leads me on."</HI> Milton.&mdash;Hem! I follow. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> STEDFAST.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>A noble hou&s;e, faith! and be&s;peaks &s;ome of that &s;tately dignity in the owner; which my friend Harry hinted to me.&mdash;His lord&s;hip, I warrant, is as &s;tiff as backram&mdash;with a pompous di&s;play of language that puz|zles a plain man to keep with him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, his Lord&s;hip &s;aid he'd be with you in the twinkling of a bed-po&s;t. <STAGE>[Exit John.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! that's the odde&s;t phra&s;e for a fine &s;poken peer, I ever met with.&mdash;The ignorance of the &s;ervant, I &s;uppo&s;e. The&s;e blockheads never know how to deliver a me&s;&s;age. Oh here he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD DUBERLY.</STAGE>
<P>&mdash;Your lord&s;hip's mo&s;t obedient.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Lord</HI> D.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(Bows vulgarly)</STAGE>
<P>Sir, you are kindly wel|come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Kindly welcome! conde&s;cending at lea&s;t; but not quite &s;o dignified as I expected.&mdash;<STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE> I am a rough traveller, my Lord, ungifted with you flow of dic|tion, and having real bu&s;ine&s;s, I tru&s;t that without further preface, it may plead my apology.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="32" REF="32">
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, aye, bu&s;ine&s;s is bu&s;ine&s;s; and words, you know butter no par&s;nips&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Butter no par&s;nips!&mdash;why he's &s;neering at my plainne&s;s;&mdash;or I have mi&s;taken the per&s;on; I have the ho|nor, I think, of addre&s;&s;ing Lord Duberly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure you have, as &s;ure as eggs is eggs. Come, mu&s;ter&mdash;mayhap you may chu&s;e a mor&s;el of &s;ummat?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not any thing, I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't &s;ay &s;o. A drop of wine, now; or a &s;neaker of punch&mdash;or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing, my Lord.&mdash;I am thunder&s;truck!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, now then for the piece of bu&s;ine&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have had &s;ome fears, my Lord, that I might be too abrupt in the di&s;clo&s;ure; but, &s;ince this introduc|tion.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, rot it! I was never for no long rigma|role, not I! an hone&s;t man's meaning, needs no flouri&s;hes. Hone&s;ty's like a good piece of roa&s;t beef, Mu&s;ter Stedfa&s;t, it lacks little garni&s;h, and the more plainer, the more pa|latable.&mdash;That's my &s;entiment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I admire your &s;entiment, my Lord;&mdash;but I can't &s;ay much for your language. <STAGE>(a&s;ide)</STAGE>&mdash;I mu&s;t inform your lord&s;hip, that no great length of time has elap&s;ed &s;ince I&mdash;don't be agitated&mdash;left Quebec, in America.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Yankee doodle, may-hap?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(ri&s;es)</STAGE>
<P>A Yankee doo!&mdash;I am no Ameri|can, my lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No offence to you,&mdash;but &s;eeing you have got a tawneyi&s;h tinge, <STAGE>(ri&s;es.)</STAGE> I thought you might be a little out-landi&s;h.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall ever be proud in being able to &s;ay that I am an Engli&s;hman; but &s;hould &s;uppo&s;e recently arrived from the country I have named, mu&s;t intere&s;t your feelings.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Intere&s;t&mdash;why what's he at? if I &s;eem not to under&s;tand, now, I &s;hall make &s;ome pleaguy hole in my manners, I warrant <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I perceive by your &s;ilence, that your lord&s;hip, is affected. A per&s;on in your &s;ituation cannot naturally be otherwi&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then it's the fa&s;hion, for a peer to be in a pucker, when any body comes from Quebec in America. <STAGE>(a&s;ide.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pray inform me, my Lord, have you received any letter from your $on, &s;ince he wrote to advi&s;e you, he had fini&s;hed the bu&s;ine&s;s which induced you to &s;end him from home, and, that, he was immediately preparing to meet you in London?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="33" REF="33">
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Since that? no, to be &s;ure.&mdash;Why, lord love you, he &s;et out directly after it, on purpo&s;e to come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>And your lord&s;hip has heard no news from any of his fellow pa&s;&s;engers?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fellow pa&s;&s;engers!&mdash;no, not I&mdash;neither in|&s;ide nor out.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;ide nor out! It's plain, however, that we are all &s;uppo&s;ed to have gone to the bottom. <STAGE>(A&s;ide)</STAGE> Know then, my Lord, I was his fellow-pa&s;&s;enger.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Was you? You are ju&s;t come up then, it &s;eems.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come up! This is an ea&s;y way of talking to a man &s;uppo&s;ed to be drowned. <STAGE>(a&s;ide).</STAGE> I am here, you &s;ee, my Lord: but Providence be prai&s;ed, it was never my fate to go down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well, that's no matter of mine. Your fate may have lain another way, to be &s;ure, as you &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Another way!&mdash;Zounds! he can't dare to in|&s;inuate, that I was born to be hanged! <STAGE>(A&s;ide.)</STAGE> He ap|pears the mo&s;t ignorant, unfeeling&mdash;Hear me, my Lord. Has your &s;on ever been dear to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plaguy dear, indeed, mu&s;ter Stedfa&s;t; only ax Doctor Panglo&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>An intimate, I &s;uppo&s;e, to whom your Lord|&s;hip has unburthened your mind, in private?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, he mends my cakelology every morning, and is moreover a great philo&s;opher.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>On &s;uch an occa&s;ion, a father might well call in philo&s;ophy to his a&s;&s;i&s;tance.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hired him a purpo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hired him!&mdash;Hired a philo&s;opher to con&s;ole him for the death of his &s;on!&mdash;Delicacy, is &s;uperfluous here, I &s;ee.&mdash;In &s;hort, my Lord, I come to inform you, your &s;on, lo&s;t as he has been to the world, has newly and unexpectedly entered into life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well; and what then?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then! The brutal apathy in this po&s;t of a Peer, makes me ready to beat him. <STAGE>(A&s;ide.</STAGE> Why then, he has this day arrived in town; here, in this metropolis.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what &s;ignifies a cock and a bull &s;tory, about what I know already.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Know it!&mdash;It mu&s;t be by in&s;piration, then. By what &s;upernatural &s;ign have you di&s;covered his arrival?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What &s;ign?&mdash;Why a Blue-boar.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord, my Lord,&mdash;ignorance&mdash;little, indeed, from the account I received from a blindly affec|tionate youth, did I expect to find it here. Ignorance may palliate meanne&s;s and buffoonery, and merely meet contempt, but want of feeling excites indignation. You
<PB N="34" REF="34">
have &s;hocked me, and I leave you. From exalted rank like yours, my Lord, men lock for exalted virtue; and when the&s;e are coupled, they command re&s;pect, and grace each other:&mdash;but the coronet, which gives and receives &s;plendour, when fixed on the brow of merit, glitters on the worthle&s;s head, like a mark of di&s;grace, to render vice, folly, and inhumanity con&s;picuous. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That there chap's mad!&mdash;he has put me all of a twitter. If my Lady had happened to be here, I'm &s;ure &s;he would have pa&s;pired with fear.&mdash;John!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> JOHN.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has the porter let out that there man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>John.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, my Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Never let him clap his damned ugly mug in the&s;e here d$ors again. He is as mad as any poor &s;oul un|der a <HI>&s;tatue</HI> of lunacy. Shut the door, d'ye hear.&mdash;Od rabbit it! if P$ers are to be frightened in this here fa&s;hion, I'd rather &s;erve &s;oap and candles again in comfort at Go&s;|port. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE IV.&mdash;<HI>Enter</HI> DICK DOWLAS <HI>and</HI> ZEKIEL HOME|SPUN.</HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but at this un&s;ea&s;onable time of&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I couldn't help it, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Isn't the fa&s;hion to pay a vi&s;it at this time of the evening&mdash;who let you in?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why a fat man in the hall, that pop't out of a leather chair, that comes all over his head like a tub.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The porter, I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Belike it was. He has ta&s;&s;els a&punc; top of his &s;houlders, and a &s;ight of binding, that looks like par&s;l$y and butter, about his wai&s;tcoat.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But why did you come now:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I do tell you, I was unea&s;y about ye, Dick, I couldn't ha' &s;taid away, if I was to be hanged for't.&mdash;You did promi&s;e to meet us, this afternoon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have been prevented; we young fellows of fa&s;hion can't an&s;wer for our hours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Dick, London fa&s;hions and friend&s;hip, I do fear, go &s;eldom cheek by jowl. I ha' ju&s;t left Cecily at the place.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and what of her, Zekiel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor &s;oul! &s;he ha' been &s;obbing, ready to bur&s;t her heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cecily in tears!&mdash;for what?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="35" REF="35">
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>All along o' you man. You did promi&s;e to come, and &s;he do tell me, &s;he never know'd you to break your word till you were made a gentleman. I &s;aid all I could to comfort her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And what did you &s;ay, Zekiel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I told her, that you had always dealt fair and open with her, 'till now&mdash;and if you could be hone&s;t to her when you were a lawyer, there might be &s;ome hope of your being &s;o now, even though you be an ho|nourable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well; I &s;hall &s;ee her to-morrow, and &s;ee you too, Zekiel; and &s;ettle &s;ome plan for her; and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plan?&mdash;why the plan be &s;ettled already&mdash;and, you do know, &s;he be in place, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!&mdash;in place will never do; I have a liking for her, you know; and when&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>A liking!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; that's a love, you know; and a regard for you, Zekiel&mdash;and, in &s;hort, a girl on whom Lord Duberly's &s;on has fixed his affections, mu&s;t not remain in &s;ervice; it would di&s;grace one of us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>It can't di&s;grace one of us, Dick.&mdash;A good girl who have lo&s;t her parents &s;upport, and do get her bread in hone&s;t indu&s;try, be a pride in&s;tead of a di&s;grace, to any one that loves her, you do know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I didn't mean that; I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Noa&mdash;noa&mdash;ble&s;s you, 'tware only your good heart run away wi' you. You do wi&s;h us well, Dick&mdash;you do wi&s;h to &s;erve us; and over&s;hot your&s;elf a little, i$ what you &s;aid, that be all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, look ye, Zekiel; you are a well-mean|ing lad&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, and &s;o be you, Dick; I ware getting a bit tiffi&s;h wi' you at the Blue-boar. I did think &s;udden pride ware going to turn you top&s;y-turvey&mdash;I was angry at my&s;elf, afterwards.&mdash;But I do beg your pardon&mdash;heartily, my good friend&mdash;faith heartily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay; hear me: 'tis fit we &s;hould under&s;tand one another&mdash;which we don't &s;eem to do&mdash;at pre&s;ent.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't us! Ecod I &s;hould be grieved at that, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Li&s;ten to me. My &s;ituation, you &s;ee, is much altered.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Woundedly indeed!&mdash;Here be a hou&s;e&mdash;and what a brave coat you ha' gotten on, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No matter; but there are &s;ituations in the world, Zekiel, that do not always tally: chance may re|move one man &s;o far from another, in the rank of life; that,
<PB N="36" REF="36">
tho' their good-will may continue, the &s;ame cu&s;tom requires, that they &s;hould not live exactly&mdash;mind, I &s;ay, not <HI>exactly,</HI> on the &s;ame footing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee what you be driving at, Dick; I &s;ee it; I did fear it, all along. Well, well, $&mdash;I do know that I be'nt fit company for a Lord's &s;on;&mdash;but when a Lord was once a Chandler, I thought indeed&mdash;no matter&mdash;ble&s;s thee, Dick.&mdash;I &s;hall always wi&s;h thee well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay; I dont mean that we &s;hould &s;epar|ate; on the contrary, I wi&s;h we may be clo&s;er in friend|&s;hip than ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, Dick! I ha' loved thee!&mdash;I'd ha' parted wi' my la&s;t farthing to&mdash;no matter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>There is no occa&s;ion to take it in this manner; we may be both rich, both happy, Zekiel: But, you know, how impo&s;&s;ible it is for the &s;on of a Peer to marry your &s;i&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ay, aye, I do &s;ee it&mdash;it be all over.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>No rea&s;on for that on earth; for though the world places a di&s;tance between Cis and me, as to matri|mony; yet it makes an allowance for every thing el&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't under&s;tand you, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My rank not permitting the u&s;ual forms be|tween us, which my regard for her happine&s;s makes me wi&s;h, could take place; all I can now do is to rai&s;e her from future fear of poverty; and we may be man and wife in every thing but the ceremony.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, now I do under&s;tand ye.&mdash;You be a ra&s;cal!&mdash;Odds fle&s;h! I &s;hall choak!&mdash;a damed ra&s;cal&mdash;keep out o' my way or I may do ye a mi&s;chief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dick, Dick!&mdash;Had a &s;tranger done this, I'd ha' knocked him down: but a dear friend, to turn traitor&mdash;<STAGE>(bur&s;ts into tears.)</STAGE>&mdash;Damme, it's too&punc; much,&mdash;I&punc; can't &s;tand it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well; but only hear me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I ha' heard too much, already&mdash;<STAGE>(To Dick.)</STAGE> Rot it! I be a&s;hamed to be &s;uch a blubberer!&mdash;But the greate&s;t &s;hame do light upon you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I begin to feel that it does, Zekiel.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And well you may. If it be the part of a Lord's &s;on to &s;tab his friend to the heart, by robbing his &s;i&s;ter of her hone&s;ty, much good may do ye, wi' your grandeur.&mdash;But let me tell your grandeur this, Mr. Dow|las; you do know &s;ome'at (little enow to be &s;ure) of the laa; and the laa of the land do make no difference between a Peer and a Ploughman&mdash;if you do dare to hurt Cecily, the laa &s;hall lay you flat, in the fir&s;t place, and my plough|man's fi&s;t, in the &s;econd!&mdash;and &s;o my &s;ervice to you. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="37" REF="37">
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My heart upbraids me. I have wounded, at one blow, an hone&s;t man, and an innocent girl, whom rea&s;on and inclination tell me to love. Now, am I &s;o mere a beginner, that whether this is, or is not fa&s;hionable, cur&s;e me, if I know; but I have been told it is. I mu&s;t go deeper into its my&s;teries, or ab&s;tain from it altogether; and, I feel &s;o much pain already, that in this &s;ame career of fa&s;hion, where feeling they &s;ay is bani&s;hed, I &s;hall make a very aukward figure. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.<STAGE>&mdash;<HI>Lady</HI> CAROLINE DORMER'S <HI>Hou&s;e.</HI></STAGE></HEAD>
<STAGE>Cecily di&s;covered &s;eated, crying, and leaning on Zekiel.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ZEKIEL.</SPEAKER>
<P>DO you, do ye cheer up a bit, &s;i&s;ter Cecily! don't ye take on &s;o&mdash;don't ye, now!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>O, Zekiel! for certain my poor heart will break.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't ye, &s;ay &s;o, Cecily, for that would go nigh to break mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I never will give ear to a lawyer's vows as long us I do breathe.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, that be what all the girls &s;ay over and over.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>A ba&s;e perjury man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That he be!&mdash;he ha' &s;tung me to the quick.&mdash;a Viper!&mdash;and offer to abu&s;e you&mdash;damn him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, don't you &s;ay that of him, Zekiel, I can't bear that, tho' he has been &s;o cruel to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then pluck up a bit of &s;pirit, now.&mdash;Pray ye do. You ha' gotten a good place you do know, and things will go well enow, I warrant us. How dos't like madam, eh, Cecily!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Purely! &s;he is &s;o tender and kind to me, Ze|kiel&mdash;Heigho!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, dry your tears, now, Cecily. I would be main glad to find madam be &s;o kind to you. What did ye do, a'ter I left you la&s;t?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why I was but poorly, Zekiel.&mdash;I had been crying you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel&punc; H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, but don't ye cry any more, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when madam Caroline &s;aw it, &s;he was &s;o kind, and &s;o comfortable to me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Was &s;he?&mdash;good &s;oul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="38" REF="38">
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;he bid me go to re&s;t&mdash;and &s;poke as &s;weet, and took as much care of me, as poor mother u&s;ed to do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s her for it, if I be ever able to make a return, I'll&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, I hear her in next room! &s;he is up! and if &s;he &s;hould catch us here. There now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cecily, child! I thought you had'nt ri&s;en.&mdash;I did'nt wi&s;h you to attend if you were unwell, my poor girl!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank you very kindly, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, your brother, I &s;ee.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>At your humble &s;ervice, madam. I made bold to call to &s;ee how &s;i&s;ter were, and to make my humble duty to you, madam. Cecily do tell me you ha' been main kind to her.&mdash;We be poor, madam, but I do hope you will be plea&s;ed to take our thanks, without offence.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Offence! hone&s;t friend!&mdash;to merit and receive the thanks of the poor, is one of the heart's be&s;t gratifications.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>She be main good-natured, indeed! I&mdash;I had a little bit of a favour to a&s;k, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it, friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why here be a &s;crap of paper here&mdash;it were poor father's&mdash;if you would be plea&s;ed to tell me if it be worth any thing, now it be &s;o old.&mdash;<STAGE>(gives a Lottery Ticket.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is worth enquiring after.&mdash;'Tis an old Lot|tery Ticket. <STAGE>(returning it.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! then it be of little good.&mdash;Father had no luck that way&mdash;but, for all mother could &s;ay, he was always a dabbling, and a dabbling. I'll &s;ee about it, at &s;hop, tho'&mdash;I do wi&s;h you a dutiful good morning, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>A good day, friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(apart to Cecily.)</STAGE> Pluck a &s;pirit, do ye now, Cecily. Gi' me a bu&s;s&mdash;there, now, let that comfort ye, a bit.&mdash;I'll call and bye.&mdash;A good day to you, madam.</P>
<STAGE>(Exit Zekiel.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>You do not look recover'd yet, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall be better in time, if you plea&s;e, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, child&mdash;you mu&s;n't give way to low &s;pirits. Your &s;ituation is new to you, indeed, but this fickle world is full of changes, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(crying)</STAGE> Oh, dear me! &s;ure enough this world is full of ficklene&s;s and change!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, but do not cry thus, child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t cry, if you plea&s;e, madam, I can't help it, indeed, I can't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor girl! does any thing pre&s;s heavy on your mind?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="39" REF="39">
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, yes, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is it? is it in my ability to relieve you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, madam.&mdash;It's quite out of your power to give me what I have lo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lo&s;t, child! have you lo&s;t any thing &s;ince you came to London?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Any thing you brought up in the coach with you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your cloaths? or a parcel? or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What then, child?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>A young man, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lo&s;t a young man, Cecily!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>He was once the true&s;t hearted youth! Law|yer Lattitat's clerk, of our town, if you plea&s;e, madam&mdash;we were to be married&mdash;Brother was agreeable to it; and now he has ba&s;ely left me, and all becau&s;e he grown rich and great.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, &s;ince la&s;t night! That is &s;omewhat &s;udden, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, I &s;hould as &s;oon look'd to have been, as to think my Dick would be made a lord's &s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Made a lord's &s;on! how, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know how they make lords &s;ons, madam&mdash;but his father has had a good fortune, by a death, and &s;o Dick is now &s;on to Lord Duberly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Duberly, good heavens! how that name agitates me! the pre&s;ent Lord Duberly, you mean, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, if you plea&s;e, madam, the la&s;t lord&mdash;Zekiel heard all from the porter&mdash;the la&s;t lord's &s;on was drowned at &s;ea, they &s;ay&mdash;perhaps you may have heard on't, madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have&mdash;I have indeed, Cecily?&mdash;<STAGE>(agitated.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh dear! an't you well, madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I&mdash;I&mdash;'$$s nothing, Cecily,&mdash;and &s;o your lover, poor wench, has de&s;erted you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, wor&s;e than that, madam, brother is al|mo&s;t out of his wi$s about it,&mdash;for he &s;aid, a ba&s;e cruel man!&mdash;He would make my fortune by ruinating me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor &s;implicity! dry your tears my good girl; and rather rejoice that you have e&s;caped the &s;nares of a profligate, you &s;hall not want protection while I can give it you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven ble&s;s you! you are very kind, madam.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><PB N="40" REF="40">
Enter <HI>KENRICK</HI> ha&s;tily.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Och, murther, murther, your very kind, ma|dam, Mi&s;s Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Och, why did'nt I die before I was born, to &s;ee this ill looking day.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what's the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>The matter' and hav'nt I trotted into Lom|bard-&s;treet, to get your draught turned into money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure&mdash;for there lies the little which I now po&s;&s;e&s;s, Kenrick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, by my &s;oul, there it lies, like my ould uncle, Dennis Kenrick, in Carrickfargus Church-yard: for we &s;hall never &s;ee it again, as long as we live.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good heavens! you alarm me!&mdash;&s;urely the hou&s;e hasn't fail'd?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, faith, the hou&s;e &s;tands an upright, ju&s;t where it did, but the old thief of a banker, has'nt a thir|teen left to ble&s;s him&s;elf with.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Broke!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, by my &s;oul, broke hor&s;e and foot&mdash;and &s;o bad, they &s;ay, that all the devils in hell can't mend him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then, indeed, I am completely ruined!</P>
<STAGE>[&s;inks in a chair.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(running to her.)</STAGE> No, don't you &s;ay &s;o, Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't grieve! my &s;weet Mi&s;s Caroline, don't grieve! Och, the devil! my ould heart's as full as a ba&s;|ket of eggs. Pray now, keep up your &s;pirits, for you have lo&s;t every farthing you have in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, the Gracious! Is that it! Pray, if you plea&s;e, Madam, don't take on &s;o, then. For I have money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>What <HI>have you</HI> money?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, that I have: and while I have ten good pounds, that poor mother left me, in my box, and a &s;ilver watch, it &s;hall never be &s;aid that I kept it from one in di&s;|tre&s;s, who has been &s;o kind to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;ha gra gal ma chree was you! what a pity it is now, that a generous heart has'nt always a heavy pur&s;e to keep it company.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>My poor girl! your grateful attachment touches me&mdash;I mu&s;t retire and think of&mdash;do not follow me, Cecily&mdash;I'll con&s;ult on mea&s;ures to&mdash;oh, providence! for what mi&s;eries am I ordained. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, I hope I hav'nt given madam offence, by what I &s;aid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="41" REF="41">
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, my &s;weet one! you're a little angel in a mob cap.&mdash;What will I do now? there's my Watch and my Buckles, and my&mdash;by my &s;oul now, I'd pawn my|&s;elf if the pawnbroker would lend me any thing upon me&mdash;come with me and con&s;ult, little one.&mdash;Faith, I hav'nt a brother, or a nephew, or a cou&s;in garman, or a father, or any (kiff or kin little bit of a kin&s;man) left to a&s;&s;i&s;t in all this botheration.&mdash;Come, little one? och! what an ould long winded bea&s;t am I, now, to have out-lived all my loving relations. <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.&mdash;<STAGE>A Chamber in an Inn.</STAGE></HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> STEDFAST <HI>and</HI> MORELAND.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be more your&s;elf, Henry. Firmne&s;s in the moment of di&s;appointment&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;appointment!&mdash;'tis torture&mdash;it racks me&mdash;Caroline fled, none knows whither&mdash;unprotected! Per|haps expo&s;ed to want too! to biting penury! The ac|count, though confu&s;ed, which I gathered la&s;t night from the unfeeling wretch in po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the late Mr. Dor|mer's hou&s;e&mdash;why not have gone to my father's&mdash;Caroline might there have relied on an a&s;&s;ylum.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Umph! perhaps not.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Stedfa&s;t! how little you know of my wor|thy father's heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I've had a &s;pecimen.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why did you prevent me from going to him la&s;t night?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>After the ill news you had ju&s;t received, at the late Mr. Dormer's, your mind was too much agitated for &s;uch an encounter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, well; you &s;ee I followed your commands. You&punc; rule me like a child, Stedfa&s;t; I went to bed, but not to re&s;t&mdash;why &s;hould'nt you then, explain every thing?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>You were unfit-to hear any thing. You were almo&s;t di&s;tracted. 'Twas &s;ufficient that I &s;ent word to Lord Duberly, that you would pay your duty to him, to|day, after breakfa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, you &s;aw my father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>I did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>And he received you with that complacency &s;o friendly a me&s;&s;enger de&s;erved.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why to &s;ay the truth, I found none of that &s;tately dignity about him, which you led me to expect.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>To you, of cour&s;e, when you explained the pur|port of your vi&s;it, he would throw that a&s;ide. The ten|derne&s;s
<PB N="42" REF="42">
of the father &s;oftened the au&s;terity of habit, and his language came warm from the heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my &s;oul, 'twould puzzle me to tell where it came from: but to do him ju&s;tice (notwith&s;tand|ing his harrangues in the Hou&s;e of Peers, which you talk'd of) his language was as little Parliamentary as any lan|guage I ever heard in my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, your's was no meeting of formality.&mdash;Bu|&s;ine&s;s like your's called for no pomp of words on either &s;ide.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Words!&mdash;no&mdash;&s;o his Lord&s;hip &s;eemed to think, when he told me they buttered no par&s;nips.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>My father! You je&s;t, &s;ure?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, I do not&mdash;and I'm afraid my dear young friend, your ardent feelings have painted the pa|rental affection of Lord Duberly, in warmer colours than it merits.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good Heaven! what do you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>To be plain, he received the account of his lo&s;t &s;on's arrival with more than coldne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, you mi&s;took my dear father's manner.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing could be le&s;s equivocal&mdash;He treated me with&mdash;but that does'nt &s;ignify&mdash;When I intro|duced my&s;elf by informing him, that I came from Que|bec&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye; that mu&s;t have excited his attention. He made a thou&s;and enquiries?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, faith. Only one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>What was that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;haw!&mdash;trivial&mdash;merely ribaldry.&mdash;Damn it, I'm a&s;hamed for his &s;ake, and your's to mention it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay; I entreat you tell me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why he a&s;ked if&mdash;p&s;haw!&mdash;if I was a yan|kee doodle, if you mu&s;t have it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>You a&s;toni&s;h me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not more than I was a&s;toni&s;hed. In &s;hort, in&s;tead of finding the fond, anxious, agitated, father, I met a man reckle&s;s of his child's fate, and treating the man who brought him the news of a &s;on's pre&s;ervation with levity and in&s;ult.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Impo&s;&s;ible! 'Tis not his nature.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, even with buffoonery.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Take care, Stedfa&s;t&mdash;you may have mi&s;con|ceived; But I mu&s;t not have my father's character made an ill-timed &s;port.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, 'tis &s;portive enough in it&s;elf, for that matter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="43" REF="43">
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Sportive!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, beyond comprehen&s;ion. He deals in witchcraft, it &s;eems;&mdash;for he was even jocular enough to tell me that he had a familiar in the &s;hape of a Blue-boar, who had given him intelligence of your arrival. I confe&s;s, I was &s;hocked.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>As I am Stedfa&s;t, &s;hocked at your attempt in a moment like this, to trifle with the feelings of a friend, and endeavour to fully a venerable character, too well e&s;tabli&s;hed to be tainted by the breath of mi&s;repre&s;enta|tion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Zounds! I tell you that Lord Du|berly&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Lord Duberly, Sir, is as incapable of the con|duct and language you have de&s;cribed, as I am incapable of hearing it without re&s;entment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;entment! you are warm, Mr. Moreland.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have rea&s;on, Sir. Look at the man&mdash;Look at Lord Duberly&mdash;his very countenance contradicts the a&s;&s;ertion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I dont know. I believed, &s;ince you &s;aid it, that gentleman was once written legibly on his brow&mdash;but damme, if time has'nt &s;cratched out the writing, as thoroughly as ever writing was &s;cratched out in the world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>This conduct of yours &s;hall not go unpuni&s;hed, Mr. Stedfa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unpuni&s;hed, young man?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, by Heaven! Such a gro&s;s a&s;per&s;ion of my good and worthy father, &s;hall be an&s;wered with the life of that man&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who lately &s;aved your's Henry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Stedfa&s;t, I&mdash;I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Young man, 'tis well for us, that winter's enough have pa&s;&s;ed over my head, to make my blood flow in a temperate current.&mdash;Did it run riot like your's, we might now be cutting one another's throats.&mdash;Would it plea&s;e you, think you, to have done me that office.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plea&s;e me! It makes me &s;hudder.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet this, now, is what the world calls &s;atis|faction. I tru&s;t, I am as little daunted with big words, and a &s;tern look, as mo&s;t men. But the true&s;t courage, Henry, is founded on rea&s;on:&mdash;and were the head oftner permitted to check the pa&s;&s;ions of the heart, there would be le&s;s fatal encounters, on fooli&s;h cau&s;es, and the peace of many a parent, wife and child might remain unbroken.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Stedfa&s;t! The man that rea&s;ons thus would &s;urely never mean to &s;port with my anxieties.&mdash;There
<PB N="44" REF="44">
mu&s;t be &s;ome mi&s;take; pray pardon me, and accompany me to my father's. A&s;&s;i&s;t me in unravelling this my&s;tery which confounds me. Can you forgive my heart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>From the very bottom of my heart, Henry:&mdash;for, however ra&s;h in it&s;elf, the impul&s;e was filial piety; and that with me will amply excu&s;e it. <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DICK DOWLAS <HI>with</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>It don't &s;ignify, Doctor; I can't re&s;t 'till I have &s;een Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's a tutor's power over a pupil in love?&mdash;Annihilated.&mdash;True tho' trite, that, <HI>"Omina vinoie amor.</HI> Ovid.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Is &s;he pretty?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's that to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing. I'm dead to the fa&s;cinations of beauty &s;ince that unguarded day of dalliance, when being full of Bacchus.&mdash;<HI>"Bacchi plenus."</HI>&mdash;Horace.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;my pocket was picked of a metal watch, at the Sceptre, in Shoe-lane.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>This is the hou&s;e. I've told you my &s;tory&mdash;and as you value my tree hundred a-year, Doctor, be ready to a&s;&s;i&s;t me, either by me&s;&s;age, letter, or&mdash;but, what a damned gig you look like?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>A gig? Umpe! that's an Eaton phra&s;e&mdash;the We&s;tmin&s;ter call it Quiz.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And you are the greate&s;t, &s;ure, that ever was di&s;patched on love's emba&s;&s;ies, from the court of cupid.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'm not proud of the po&s;t. Take my coun|cil, and drop the pur&s;uit. <HI>"Refrain, de&s;i&s;t, de&s;ine."</HI>&mdash;Terence.&mdash;Hem&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, look'ye, doctor,&mdash;I've done an injury to two worthy &s;ouls; and I can't re&s;t till I've made re|paration. We are all of us wrong, at times, doctor, but a man doubles his ill-conduct, when he is too proud to make an apology for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yet, confe&s;&s;ing our faults, Mr. Dowla&s;s&mdash;<HI>Dick D.</HI> Is only &s;aying in other words, Doctor, that we were wi&s;er to day, than we were ye&s;terday.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Plenty of precedents, however, for your con|duct&mdash;<HI>"At lovers perjuries they &s;ay</HI>&mdash;"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, what do they &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>"They &s;ay Jove laughs."</HI> Sheak&s;peare&mdash;Hem! Phaon left Sappho; The&s;eus, Ariadne, Demo|phoon, Phyllis, Oneas, Dido.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="45" REF="45">
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Damn Dido.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn Dido?&mdash;Well, damn Dido?&mdash;with all my heart. She was daughter to King Belus of Tyre; but as very a virago&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, we need not go &s;o far for examples&mdash;now knock at that door? <STAGE>(Pointing to M. D.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Double?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! no; you'll &s;poil all&mdash;a &s;neaking &s;ingle tap, like a dun, doctor.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Like a dun? I know the knock well, Mr. Dowlas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when 'tis given, get out of the way for a while.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My con&s;tant cu&s;tom on &s;uch an occa&s;ion.&mdash;<HI>(Knocks, M. D.)</HI> There's the thorough thump of a cre|ditor.&mdash;<HI>"I never heard it, but I ran away upon in&s;tinct."</HI> Shake&s;peare.&mdash;Hem! <STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>CECILY, DICK</HI> is forward with his back towards her.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, &s;ure &s;omebody knock'd&mdash;I &s;ee nobody but that gentleman, neither&mdash;it could not be he, for if footman thump &s;o loud, for certain, your gentlefolks mu&s;t beat the door down&mdash;Was it you that knock'd, pray, Sir? <STAGE>(Dick turns round, Cecily &s;creams.)</STAGE> Don't come near me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Cecily!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Dick, Dick! <STAGE>(cries and falls in his arms.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot bear this, your tears go to my very &s;oul, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis you have been the cau&s;e of them, you have almo&s;t cut my poor heart in two.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My own &s;uffers for it &s;ufficiently, believe me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>How could you be &s;o barbarous to me? but, indeed, indeed, I forgive you.&mdash;Your cruelty will co&s;t me many a tear, but this is the la&s;t time I &s;hall ever upbraid you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I de&s;erve all your reproaches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I had come to fortune, and you had been poor, Dick, I would have flown to you, and cheered you in your poverty&mdash;I would have poured my gold at your feet; I would have &s;hared all my joys with you, and told you, that riches could never change my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And I come now, to &s;hare all mine with you, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no, Dick! my lot is very humble, but I &s;corn the gold that would buy my hone&s;ty. We mu&s;t never, never, meet any more: but indeed, indeed, I do
<PB N="46" REF="46">
truly wi&s;h you may be pro&s;perous, though you &s;ought my ruin. Ble&s;s you, Dick: and if ever poor Cecily comes into your mind, think that &s;he pray to Heaven to forgive you, for trying to harm her innocence, who&s;e greate&s;t ble&s;|&s;ing would have been, to make you happy <STAGE>(Going.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, &s;tay, and hear me; I entreat you, I come to &s;ue your pardon&mdash;I come in repentance, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And <HI>do</HI> you repent?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do; mo&s;t earne&s;tly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>That is &s;ome comfort to me. For your own heart will be ea&s;ier, and I &s;hall bear my hard lot better, now. For I know your great friends will never let you &s;toop to one in my &s;tation. Ah! times are much changed with us, Dick!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>However changed, they &s;hall not now alter my purpo&s;e, Cecily, I have been dazzled, and I have wounded you, I have covered my&s;elf too, with &s;hame and confu|&s;ion; but if they can make atonement, my fortune, my heart, and my hand, are all at your &s;ervice.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your hand! I,&mdash;I, &s;hall be able to &s;peak more &s;oon&mdash;oh! Dick!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, dear Cecily, I ro&s;e &s;trangely to rank; and I &s;hall, now, perhaps, in the eyes of the great world, &s;trangely &s;upport it; for, I am afraid Cis, that half your young fellows of fa&s;hion, would rather &s;eem wicked than ridiculous; but I &s;hall never, for the future, think that marrying a worthy woman, whom chance has placed be|neath us in life, can be any di&s;grace, while &s;educing her is reckoned among profligate fops, a matter of triumph.&mdash;Dry, dry your tears, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>The&s;e are not like the tears I &s;hed a while ago&mdash;they are tears of joy, Dick!&mdash;Hark! I am called.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>One moment,&mdash;tell me you forgive me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Forgive you! Oh, Dick&mdash;you have made me happy! how this will comfort my poor Zekiel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hall be a&s;hamed to meet him again, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I will tell him all&mdash;and&mdash;hark! I'm called again.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Adien! I will &s;ee you very, very &s;oon. Fare|well!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good bye&mdash;and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, ki&s;s&mdash;and&mdash;good bye. <STAGE>(Exit Cis.)</STAGE>&mdash;That one ki&s;s of lovely virtue is worth a million of times more, than all the blandi&s;hments that wealth and luxury can purcha&s;e.&mdash;Where the devil, now, is this doctor? I am brimfull of joy, and I have nobody to communicate my&mdash;
<STAGE><PB N="47" REF="47">
<HI>Enter</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS.</STAGE>
oh! you are returned&mdash;embrace me, doctor. Open wide your arms, in friendly congra$ulation and embrace, you prig of a tutor, the happie&s;t fellow in chri&s;tendom.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me!&mdash;why we're in the middle of the &s;treet!&mdash;Decorum, Mr. Dowlas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Damn decorum; I'm out of my &s;en&s;es.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven forbid! for it would be as clear a nine hundred a year out of my pocket, as ever man lo&s;t in his life.&mdash;What's the news?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>The news? why I am going to be married.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Married! mercy on me! Then he's mad, indeed&mdash;<HI>"Tr$bus anticyris caput in&s;anab$le."</HI>&mdash;Horace.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Con&s;ider the&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha&mdash;I'v no time to&mdash;come&mdash;come with me to my father's&mdash;I'll explain to him&mdash;and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only reflect&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Reflect! look'ye here, you grave mu&s;tard-pot of a philo&s;opher,&mdash;you &s;hall dance a jig down the &s;treet with me, to &s;hew your &s;ympathy in my happine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>A Doctor of Laws dance a jig in the open &s;treet!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Foot it&mdash;"Over the hills and far away."</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h you were far away, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dance&mdash;dance&mdash;or damn me I cut off your three hundred a year in a twinkling.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P><HI>Will you?&mdash;oh, the</HI>&mdash;"a flouri&s;h of trum|pets." <HI>Shake&s;peare&mdash;Hem!</HI>&mdash;"Over the hills and far away."&mdash;<STAGE>[Exit hand and hand, &s;inging and dancing.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2>
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE I.&mdash;<STAGE>A Street.</STAGE></HEAD>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>KENRICK.</SPEAKER>
<P>TO be &s;ure misfortune isn't a neat touch&s;tone to try friend&s;hip upon. Faith, now, all my loving friends de|&s;erve a decent kicking; and, by my &s;oul, I believe they expected it from my hands; for I no &s;onner &s;aid the word "lend"&mdash;but they all turned their backs to me. How my poor ould bones ache&mdash;and &s;ure the bigge&s;t bone about me is in my heart, for that aches more than all the other half of my body. Och, my poor Mi&s;s Caroline$ what will I do, now your aground, to keep your pretty little chin above water! If we could have kept the brave
<PB N="48" REF="48">
Mr. Henry Moreland's chin above water, now; but he's gone&mdash;he's gone; and twenty humane &s;ocieties could'nt bring him back.&mdash;I'll make bold ju&s;t to re&s;t me a bit at this door. Don't be frightened, good gentleman within, for I an't coming to borrow any money from you. <STAGE>[Sits down at door.]</STAGE> Faith, this &s;tep is like my dear friends hearts; for, by St. Patrick. it's as could and hard as a hail&s;tone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, nay be patient, Henry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear friend 'tis impo&s;&s;ible. The blow is too great; &s;o good &s;o kind a father lo&s;t! and his death &s;o &s;trangely explained to me! indeed, indeed Stedfa&s;t, my &s;pirit is almo&s;t broken.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>I can't &s;ee their faces, now, but &s;ure the&s;e two mu&s;t be a rich man that won't lend, and a borrower; for one is trotting about in great di&s;tre&s;s, and t'other as cool as a cucumber.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come, Henry; the encounter was a &s;trange one, 'tis true; and the &s;hock &s;udden. When you entered a father's hou&s;e, and prepared to leap into a fa|ther's arms, to meet that low wretch, who has cau&s;ed all our mi&s;takes, was indeed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, it di&s;tracts me! &s;o many things are floating in my di&s;ordered mind; I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>But 'tis nece&s;&s;ary you &s;hou'd be collected, now, ab&s;olutely nece&s;&s;ary. You mu&s;t do &s;peedy ju&s;tice to your|&s;elf&punc; to the memory of your departed father. How came you not to di&s;cover your&s;elf to that lump of ignorance, who has jump'd into your inheritance?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>I was &s;taggered; I heard enough from him to unravel all; and 'tis well perhaps, we withdrew &s;o abruptly, I might have done &s;omething ra&s;h at the moment. Oh, Stedfa&s;t, I &s;hall &s;ink under it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>For &s;hame, Henry! fye on this weakne&s;s! Sink under it! Decent &s;orrow for a near lo&s;s is amiable; and mode&s;t nature never looks more lovely, than when the filial tear &s;teals gently on the tomb of a parent: but de&s;|perate grief outrages manhood and religion; for in the trials, which we all are born to undergo, Henry, the man and the chri&s;tian forgets his duties to providence, and to him&s;elf, when he lo&s;es his re&s;ignation and his fortitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are an able and kind coun&s;ellor, my friend&punc; I will endeavour to be more firm.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, let us go back to our hotel: you may there compo&s;e your&s;elf.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(gets up)</STAGE> So, having taken a re&s;t, I'll go home with my bad news to con&s;ole poor Mi&s;s Caroline. <STAGE>(comes forward)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="49" REF="49">
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;eeing Kenrick.)</STAGE> I cannot be mi&s;taken in that face&mdash;eh? Kenrick!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh? why &s;ure it can't be! &s;ure my ould eyes are &s;o bad, that I &s;ee what's invi&s;ible!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>It is he! Oh, Kenrick! my good old man, tell me where is my Caroline?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Och, faith it's him&s;elf, it's him&s;elf, it's him|&s;elf!&mdash;&s;afe, &s;ound, and dry, without a wet rag about him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>But inform me, my hone&s;t Kenrick of&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hubbaboo! hubbaboo! och, I'll go wild! I'll go, mad! don't &s;peak to me yet, my dear &s;weet Mr. Henry! och, good luck to the day when your honour walk'd a&s;hore after you were drowned:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>But tell me Kenrick, of&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes&mdash;I'll tell you, I'll tell you of&mdash;och, up|on my &s;oul, you mu&s;t wait abit: I believe I was drowned my&s;elf&mdash;for the &s;alt-water runs out of my eyes by pail|fulls.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor fellow!&mdash;an old &s;ervant of Mr. Dormer'$ I &s;uppo&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well now &s;peak, Kenrick&mdash;oh, tell me is Ca|roline &s;afe?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>In troth, and &s;he is!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Thank Heaven!&mdash;And in London?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, in this wide dirty town; and big as it is, there isn't a thirteen to be had, for love or money, to help her out of her di&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Her di&s;tre&s;s! But I feared it. Let me fly to her; and&mdash;you are &s;urely with her &s;till, Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>With her! and is it your&s;elf, Mr. Henry, that can a&s;k Kenrick &s;uch a que&s;tion? or would I leave my friends in their need, that &s;upported me in their pro&s;|perity?&mdash;Och, the devil fly away with him that would I &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hone&s;t fellow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Pardon me, my good hone&s;t Kenrick.&mdash;I know not what I &s;ay, Conduct me to her, and you &s;hall ex|plain all by the way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Conduct you! faith, ould as I am, I'll go hopping over all the kennels home with you, as nimble as a jack-daw.&mdash;Och, St. Patrick be prai&s;ed.</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come then, Stedfa&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Stedfa&s;t.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Henry. I'll &s;ee you to the door of Mi&s;s Dormer, and then leave you. And on this occa&s;ion, my dear friend, let me heartily congratulate you. Such an event as this, comes mo&s;t opportunely; and it may
<PB N="50" REF="50">
prove to you Henry, in this chequered life of joy and &s;orrow, that Providence has ever &s;ome balm in &s;tore to pour into the wounds that it inflicts; and that the wor&s;t of griefs may be a&s;&s;uaged by the pity power who cha&s;tens us! <STAGE>[Exeunt.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE II.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD <HI>and</HI> LADY DUBERLY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But li&s;ten, my lady, to rea&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then I mu&s;t'nt li&s;ten to you, My Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Um&mdash;why I've been almo&s;t &s;cared out of my &s;even &s;en&s;es, for certain. The old man that was here la&s;t night, ru&s;hed in with another young one with him, this morning. I can't make head nor tail of what he wants for my part. But, as to Dick, he'll certainly break his heart, if he does'nt marry this here wench.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wonder, my Lord, you can think of &s;uch a thing&mdash;A Peer's &s;on to marry a maid-&s;ervant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Od rabbit it, my lady, now don't be ob&s;tra|pulous. You know when his father married you, you was but a clear-&s;tarcher.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's quite another &s;ort of an affair; and you might have more manners than to mention it now; but as to learning you elegance&mdash;ah! we may take the hor&s;e to the water, but there's no making him drink.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, I'm &s;ure I did'nt mean any di&s;parage|ment to you&mdash;for you was counted, on all hands, the be&s;t getter-up of &s;mall linen, in our town. Here's the doctor, let's ax his advice in this here bu&s;ine&s;s.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS.</STAGE>
<P>Pray now, doctor,&mdash;you mu&s;t know we're in a bit of a quandiary, doctor.</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your Lord&s;hip had better be in an uncertainty?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, lord love you, &s;o I am, mum. Pray did'nt you never hear of no great man that was married to a farmer's daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Walter&mdash;a marquis of Lombardy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>There, my lady! what do you think of that? damn it, if the Marquis &s;mou&s;ed Grizzle, Dick may mar$y the maid &s;ervant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My pupil!&mdash;Zounds, my &s;alary&mdash;<HI>"Tre|mor occupat artus."</HI> Virgil&mdash;hem!&mdash;my income totters!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And in that there ca&s;e, doctor, your three hundred a year, mu&s;t go to the mending of my Cakelology.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="51" REF="51">
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>But I &s;hall lo&s;e&mdash;no, thing:&mdash;<HI>a Lap&s;us linguoe.</HI>&mdash;One annuity gone with my pupil! Then I've only "clear for life, <HI>&s;ix</HI> hundred pounds a year" Swift.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(Apart to Panglo&s;s.)</STAGE> You know, Doctor, my three hnndred &s;tops, the moment my &s;on marries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Does it? Oh, Jupiter, if ever contradiction crept into the bo&s;om of beauteous woman&mdash;<HI>"Mulier &s;or|mo&s;a."</HI> Horace.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Stuff a double do&s;e into that ter|rible old woman, and &s;ave the fortunes of Peter Panglo&s;s. Here he comes.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DICK DOWLASS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, father, has my mother made up her mind?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I can't tell Dick.&mdash;my lady &s;eems be|twixt and betweeni&s;h, as a body may &s;ay. But it all de|pends upon her vardick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, &s;he is but a farmer's daughter, they &s;ay, and what's a farmer, my dear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, an Engli&s;h farmer, mother, is one who &s;upports his family and &s;erves his country, by his own indu&s;try in this land of commerce.&mdash;Mother, &s;uch a cha|racter will be always re&s;pectable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's right, Dick&mdash;Father's own &s;on to a hair. When I kept my &s;$op at Go&s;port, I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h my lord.&mdash;Well you&mdash;you w$re always my darling, you know, Dick; and, I can't find in my heart to give you a denial.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Can't you! I wi&s;h you could find it in your tongue.&mdash;Six hundred a year, blown away by the breath of that Sybyl.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>That's my good mother, you've made me &s;o happy, I, zounds, I &s;hall run mad.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zounds! and &s;o &s;hall I.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>A thou&s;and thanks, my dear mother, and my dear father, too; I'll get as drunk as&mdash;wi&s;h me joy, Doctor&mdash;wi&s;h me joy a hundred times!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>A hundred times!&mdash;I feel, Mr. Dowla&s;s, on this occa&s;ion, &s;ix hundred times more than I know how to expre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And if you would but indulge me now, in let|ting me conduct you to Cecily&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Odd rot it, my Lady, let's humour Dick for once. The young ones like to be cooing and bui$ding, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why the coach, I believe, is at the door, my lord. <STAGE>[Exit with Lord Duberly.</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="52" REF="52">
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Is it? hobs then, my lady, let'$ bundle, Dick,&mdash;come Doctor&mdash;Now you mus'nt make me ride backwards, my lady,&mdash;for you know I ha'nt been u&s;ed to a coach, and I &s;hall certainly be qualmi&s;h if you do.&mdash;Come my lady!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Doctor, we lo&s;e time?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Time!&mdash;lo&s;e!&mdash;I've lo&s;t as pretty a pair of &s;nug annuities as&mdash;let me &s;ee&mdash;<HI>"Take &s;ix from nine."</HI>&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>"And three remains." <HI>Cocker.&mdash;Hem!</HI></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come&mdash;it's late?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only three?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Only three! why it's only twelve, man; but come, if you don't attend to my father better, I can tell you he'll kick you and your three hundred a year to the devil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will he?&mdash;<HI>"Oh, for a hou&s;e with wings?"</HI>&mdash;Shake&s;peare&mdash;Hem!&mdash;I fly, Mr. Dowlas.</P>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3>
<HEAD>SCENE III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> CECILY <HI>with</HI> CAROLINE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed, I truly hope you are better, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>I have little rea&s;on to be &s;o, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, I hope you have! and if the wor&s;t comes to the wor&s;t&mdash;but I'm almo&s;t a&s;ham'd to tell you, madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Innocence, like yours, my good girl, can know nothing it &s;hould fear to reveal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I needn't be much afraid, neither&mdash;for it's what a power of folks, rich and poor, do come to at la&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What's that, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wedlock, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed! this is unexpected, after what you told me this morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, but you know, Madam, as to wedlock, and all that, many things fall out between the cup and the lip, as they &s;ay.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(&s;ighing.)</STAGE> 'Tis too true, indeed, Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o my Dick came to our door, Madam; 'tis but a little while agone&mdash;and his dear eyes were as full of tears! and you know that was a pity, Madam&mdash;for his eyes are &s;o fine and &s;o blue, 'tis a &s;hame any thing &s;hould &s;poil 'em.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And &s;o we &s;oon brought matters to bear, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>How, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why he looked &s;o &s;orry that it made my heart bleed to &s;ee him&mdash;and when I love him &s;o dearly, it would
<PB N="53" REF="53">
be cruel not to marry him when he a&s;ked me. Don't you think &s;o, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>May you be very, very happy!&mdash;'tis an ea&s;e to my mind, in the mid&s;t of my misfortunes, to know that you will be provided for. I was on the point of tel|ling you, Cecily, that my reduced circum&s;tances would not permit me to keep you with me any longer.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear! and was you going to be &s;o un|kind to me, Madam?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Unkind to you my good girl! oh, no! it would have to have &s;ent forth &s;implicity like yours, unpro|tected.&mdash;But hard nece&s;&s;ity!&mdash;I rejoice my good Cecily, rejoice &s;incerely in your good fortunes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Madam! I &s;hould rejoice more at my good fortune, if you would but let me do what I've been thinking on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is that, Cecily?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I hope you won't be angry at what I'm going to &s;ay, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, impo&s;&s;ible! &s;peak freely.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you know, Madam, Dick's a lord's &s;on; and when I am his wife, I may do fa&s;t as I plea&s;e, for rich folks wives, I have heard &s;ay, do ju&s;t what they plea&s;e in London.&mdash;Now, if you would but be &s;o good, when I'm married, as to let me &s;erve you for nothing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>No more, no more, Cecily;&mdash;I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And when my hu&s;band gives me any money, if you would be but &s;o kind as $o borrow it of me, I &s;hould be very much obliged to you, indeed, Madam!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! you have overpowered me. <STAGE>(falls on Ce|cily's neck.)</STAGE> Oh, Heaven!&mdash;how pure are all thy creatures endowed with rea&s;on, 'till worldly habits corrupt them!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>[Zekiel &s;ings without&mdash;Tol, lol, de$rol, lol!]</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>What is that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Twas brother Zekiel's voice, &s;ure.&mdash;He can't think to make &s;uch a noi&s;e here!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>Enter <HI>ZEKIEL</HI> capering and &s;inging.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tol, de rol, lol, lol!&mdash;Tol, lol, de rol, lol, lol?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mercy, Zekiel!&mdash;why you mu&s;t be crazy, &s;ure.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Zooks! and &s;o I be, &s;i&s;ter.&mdash;Tol, lol, de rol?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Think where you are, brother.&mdash;There's Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Rabbit it, Madam, I do mo&s;t humbly crave pardon&mdash;but I be in &s;uch flu&s;tration!&mdash;I ha' got&mdash;I ha'
<PB N="54" REF="54">
got&mdash;Tol, de rol, lol!&mdash;I ha' got Twenty Thou&s;and Pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>My gracious! Twenty Thou&s;and Pounds:</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tol, lol, de rol, lol!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>But &s;tand &s;till, now, brother Zekiel&mdash;where did you get &s;uch a &s;ight of money?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I' the lottery, la&s;s!&mdash;i'$he lottery.&mdash;Let me take a bit of breath.&mdash;I do crave pardon, madam.&mdash;Fa|ther's ticket&mdash;let me take a bit of&mdash;have come a prize of&mdash;a bit of breath&mdash;dear, dear, madam, heaven &s;end this luck do not &s;et my &s;imple brain a madding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Compo&s;e your&s;elf, hone&s;t friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>I do humbly thank you, madam.&mdash;I ha'&mdash;run all the way&mdash;from Lottery Office, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well, and what will you do with all this money, Zekiel?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>What will I do wi' it, Si&s;ter Cecily! Why what &s;hould a man do wi' his riches? I will fir&s;t provide for &s;uch as I do love, and then, lend a helping hand to them as be poor about me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear brother, that's ju&s;t the thing!&mdash;Come here, Zekiel&mdash;poor Madam has fallen into great trouble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Has &s;he?&mdash;How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why all her friends are dead it &s;eems.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Poor &s;oul!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And her banker hole all the money &s;he had, this very morning, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't ye &s;ay any more, &s;i&s;ter Cecily, hum!&mdash;madam&mdash;I&mdash;I be main glad to hear you be tumbled into misfortune&mdash;madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Glad, friend!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Main glad, indeed! becau&s;e you ha' been &s;o kind to &s;i&s;ter&mdash;and I be able now to return you the favour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, no more of that, Zekiel&mdash;you di&s;tre&s;s me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>With &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion, Madam, I want to take away your di&s;tre&s;s. Here, Madam&mdash;<STAGE>[pulling out bank notes.]</STAGE>&mdash;Here be a hundred&mdash;and there be a five hundred&mdash;and there be a&mdash;Rabbit it! my hand do &s;hake too much to &s;tand counting. I will &s;pread 'em all upon a table here&mdash;Take what you do want, Madam, and welcome; and thank you too, Madam.</P>
<STAGE>[&s;preading them on the table in a gr$at flurry.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>I cannot&mdash;I cannot think friend, of&mdash;<STAGE>(Both.)</STAGE> Pray ye do, now, Madam&mdash;pray ye do!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> LORD <HI>and</HI> LADY DUBERLY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ble&s;s me,&mdash;who's this?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Beg pardon, Madam, but the landlady bid u$ bundle up,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="55" REF="55">
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your commands with me, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why the whole preamble of this affair is, that my Lady and I&mdash;&s;peak to the gentlewoman my lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, you have a head, and &s;o has a pin.&mdash;We made bold to pay our re&s;pects, madam, having a little bu&s;ine&s;s concerning a female of your family.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>To whom have I the honour of &s;peaking, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you've the honour of &s;peaking to Lord Duberly, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>What! <STAGE>(gathers up the Notes ha&s;tily, and comes forward.)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>To Lord Duberly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>But Dick's coming up, with Dr. Panglo&s;s hard at his heels, and they'll tell you the long and the &s;hort on't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>What, Dick Dowlas;&mdash;Then you be the old chandler they ha' made a lord on?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Old chandler, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Look ye, my lord Soap and candles&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Soap and Candles!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;on had better keep clear o' me, I can tell him that.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DOCTOR PANGLOSS <HI>and</HI> DICK DOWLAS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cecily, let me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand off, Mr. Dowlas! &s;tand off&punc;&mdash;to think to come here to&mdash;od rabbit it! my fingers do itch to be at you. Keep you behind me, &s;i&s;ter Cecily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear Zekiel, I&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Don't you hear me? I put little tru&s;t in fair words with foul actions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear now, you are &s;o ha&s;ty, Zekiel!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hold your peace, Cecily. The be&s;t he that ever wore a head, had better be hanged than venture to harm you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Cecily I find has not explained. I'm here Ze|kiel, to make reparation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>You ha' &s;tung me to the quick, you know you have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;hare with you in all the pain, Zekiel, which I have &s;o wantonly inflicted; my heart &s;mote me, even before you left me; and every little reflection convinced me, that in the vanity of &s;udden fortune, I had offered you and the woman of my heart, a bitter injury. I am thought|le&s;s, Zekiel, but not deliberately ba&s;e; and, if you can, once more take to your bo&s;om, a guilty, but repentant friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="56" REF="56">
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Dick, Dick! <STAGE>(runs and embraces him.)</STAGE> my old companion! ah, Dick, that be a &s;tony bo&s;om that can &s;hut out an old friend, that be truly grieved for his faults, and do &s;ue for mercy.&mdash;It be more than I can do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Dear, I'm &s;o happy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>You have made my heart many a pound the lighter, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>And my own, too, Zekiel; and to prove my &s;incerity, my father and mother here, are come with an offer of my hand to Cecily.&mdash;Father&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, my Lady here, is a little upon the grumpy order for his calling us chandlers. But for my part, I don't value that of a button. A man needn't take no affront to be told he was born low, when he has got better in the world without no di&s;hone&s;ty.&mdash;There, chil|dren, be happy together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why now, that's hearty, and as luck be apt to turn wi' us along&mdash;why I ha' gotten twenty thou&s;and pounds, and I warrant Cecily &s;hall ha' &s;ome'at hand&s;ome, to&s;s'd in at the wedding.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Twenty thou&s;and pounds!&mdash;<STAGE>[goes forward to Zekiel.]</STAGE> Sir, as you will now need a tutor, to u&s;her you into life, three hundred per annum, are the trifling terms of your obedient &s;ervant, Peter Panglo&s;s, L. L. D. and A. double S.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>How!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Cecily H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, all in the lottery&mdash;I'll tell you.</P>
<STAGE>[They retire up.</STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> KENRICK.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Stand out of the way! He's coming, my dear Mi&s;s Caroline, he's coming.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who, Kenrick?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis him&s;elf! 'tis him&s;elf&mdash;he'e alive, and leaping up &s;tairs, like a &s;almon out of the water.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who do you mean?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>My dear, young, lo&s;t ma&s;ter; 'tis Mr. Henry him&s;elf, madam.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MORELAND.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Henry! Oh &s;upport me. <STAGE>(faints)</STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Caroline! oh, let me cla&s;p you to my heart, and &s;helter you there for ever.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, zounds! that's the young &s;uckling madman as &s;cared me out of my &s;en&s;es with the old one, this morning.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="57" REF="57">
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>O ble&s;s 'em both! may they live to be happy to the end of the world, and a thou&s;and years after it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P><STAGE>(recovering.)</STAGE> This is too much! oh, Hen|ry! do we once more meet! and after&mdash;by what miracle have you e&s;caped?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Kenrick.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;atisfied ma'am, for he's too much bother'd to talk. But you &s;ee he's here, and that's enough&mdash;the true, long lo&s;t, Mr. Henry Moreland.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Eh? what? Henry Moreland! Why, zounds! the late Lord Duberly's lo&s;t heir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Son and heir to that revered and re&s;pected man, be a&s;&s;ured Sir. You have done me the favour to be my <HI>tocum tenens</HI> in my ab&s;ence, and I am now return'd to re|lieve you from further trouble.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what the devil! have I only been a kind of peer's warming-pan after all&mdash;ju&s;t pop'd in to keep his place from getting cold, 'till he jump'd into it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing more, believe me. I have witne&s;&s;es &s;ufficient, &s;hould it be nece&s;&s;ary to identify my per&s;on in a minute.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Od rabbit it, then old Daniel Dowlas is no longer a Lord.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor Deborah Dowlas, a Lady.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor Dick Dowlas an Honourable.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nor Peter Panglo&s;s a tutor.&mdash;<HI>"Now, thank Heaven</HI>&mdash;"</P>
</SP>
<STAGE>"That I'm not worth a ducat." <HI>Otway.</HI></STAGE>
<P>&mdash;Hem!</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then it do &s;eem at la&s;t, Dick, that I be the rich man, and you the poor, od rabbit it! I be glad on't! for I can now plea&s;e my&s;elf wi' &s;erving my friends.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Who is this, my Caroline?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>An hone&s;t creature, Henry.&mdash;Brother to this &s;imple girl.&mdash;Their affection to me in my di&s;tre&s;s, has been mo&s;t piercing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>Then it &s;hall not go unrewarded, my Caroline.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>Wi' humble &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion, Sir, kindne&s;s to a fellow creature in di&s;tre&s;s do reward it&s;elf.&mdash;Thanks to the Lottery, we be rich, enow.&mdash;But as Dick Dowlas be to marry Cecily, if you would ju&s;t lend me a helping hand, for his father and mother here.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh re&s;t contented, hone&s;t friend, I &s;hall not di&s;|po&s;&s;e&s;s them without making a proper provi&s;ion.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>My Lord.&mdash;Hem!&mdash;<STAGE>(To Henry.)</STAGE>&mdash;if a boy &s;hould ble&s;s your nuptials, which is now &s;hortly to take place, he will certainly require a tutor.&mdash;Three hundred per annum are the terms of your Lord&s;hip's ob&s;equious &s;ervant, Peter Panglo&s;s, E. E. D. and A, double S.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="58" REF="58">
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>You are not one of tho&s;e, Sir, it &s;eems who lo&s;e an appointment for want of an early application for it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>The human mind, my lord, naturally looks forward,&mdash;<HI>"anum us pactviuet fultura,"</HI> Cicero&mdash;Hem.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>If I &s;hould need &s;uch a per&s;on, Sir, depend upon it, I &s;hould be very particular in my choice&mdash;for I &s;u&s;pect there are &s;ome among&s;t tho&s;e to whom youth is entru&s;ted who bring the character of a tutor into $i&s;repute&mdash;and draw ridicule upon a re&s;pectable &s;ituation, in which many men of learning and probity are placed.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dr. Pan.</SPEAKER>
<P>This will never do for me. Again mu&s;t I retire to Milk-alley, and &s;pin my brain for &s;ub&s;i&s;tence. <HI>"Panglos's occupations gone!"</HI>&mdash;Shake&s;peare&mdash;Hem!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>More.</SPEAKER>
<P>In calmer moments, my Caroline, I will explain the circum&s;tances of my pre&s;ervation, and when I have paid the mournful tribute due to a much lamented father, let me call you mine, and place you above the reach of fu|ture &s;orrow.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Caroline.</SPEAKER>
<P>Little &s;orrow can reach me, when you are &s;afe, Henry.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Zekiel H.</SPEAKER>
<P>And we'll get into the country&mdash;Take a bit of a farm&mdash;and all be as merry as grigs, Dick.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dick D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Agreed, Zekiel, come Cecily, I have &s;een enough already of &s;plendour, to &s;eek for happine&s;s in qui|eter &s;cenes, and I have learn't, Zekiel, that, in &s;pite of all the allurements which riches or titles may boa&s;t&mdash;the mo&s;t &s;olid and valuable po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion, is, a true friend.&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>END OF THE PLAY.</TRAILER>
